00:03:45.650 --> 00:03:47.590
have some sense of what
value investing is.

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:51.430
But there are core principles
to value investing,

00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:53.600
which we lay out in the book.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:57.060
I think a lot of it's captured
pretty well in this quote

00:03:57.060 --> 00:04:01.240
from Will Brown
from Tweedy, Browne.

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:03.390
"Our entire process is
rooted in Ben Graham's

00:04:03.390 --> 00:04:05.880
simple philosophical
framework for investing.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:08.694
He believed there were two
values for every stock,

00:04:08.694 --> 00:04:10.110
the first being
the current market

00:04:10.110 --> 00:04:12.340
price, and the second what
the share would be worth

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:13.960
if the entire
company were acquired

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:17.000
by a knowledgeable buyer, or
if the assets were liquidated,

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.120
the liabilities paid off,
and the proceeds paid

00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:20.260
to stockholders.

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:22.040
He called that the
intrinsic value,

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:23.520
and argued that
the time to buy was

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:25.920
when there was a large spread
between the current price

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:28.010
and that value, and
the time to sell

00:04:28.010 --> 00:04:29.942
was when the spread was narrow."

00:04:29.942 --> 00:04:31.650
"Over time we've
developed different ways

00:04:31.650 --> 00:04:34.480
of applying that, by valuing
income streams rather than just

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:36.890
assets, by calculating
private market values,

00:04:36.890 --> 00:04:38.360
by investing internationally.

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:40.776
But the essence of what we
do has remained consistent.

00:04:40.776 --> 00:04:42.150
Our work every
day is essentially

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:45.390
directed valuing what
businesses are worth."

00:04:45.390 --> 00:04:48.120
Now, that may seem
kind of obvious,

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:51.420
but the ability
to value a company

00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:54.640
intelligently is not
a trivial exercise,

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:58.370
but it is kind of the
fundamental thing you have

00:04:58.370 --> 00:04:59.800
to master and you
have to do well

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:02.507
to truly be a
successful investor.

00:05:02.507 --> 00:05:04.340
That's not to say there
aren't other reasons

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:06.360
why people buy stocks.

00:05:06.360 --> 00:05:09.630
People buy stocks because my
wife works at the company,

00:05:09.630 --> 00:05:12.160
I think it's a great company,
or I love the product,

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:15.582
or I heard at a cocktail party
that it was going to go up.

00:05:15.582 --> 00:05:17.040
Lots of stocks get
bought that way,

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:21.680
but that's not what
fundamental value investors do.

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:24.110
So one of the first
concepts we talk about

00:05:24.110 --> 00:05:27.580
is this notion of
circle of competence.

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:31.206
And that is what are the--
every investor should think

00:05:31.206 --> 00:05:32.830
about OK, what are
the industries, what

00:05:32.830 --> 00:05:35.940
are the situations, what are
the geographic areas, what

00:05:35.940 --> 00:05:39.100
are the size of companies
that I'm going to look at

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:42.840
and I'm going to become an
expert in that will allow me

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:50.610
to get an edge over what
is a very efficient market?

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:53.630
And I think the basic
concept is explained really

00:05:53.630 --> 00:05:55.600
well in this quote from
Julian Robertson who's

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:57.790
one of the best, most
successful hedge fund

00:05:57.790 --> 00:05:59.370
managers of all time.

00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:01.420
"A baseball player
never really gets paid,

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:03.020
no matter how many
home runs he hits

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:04.760
or what his batting
average is unless he

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:06.190
gets to the big leagues.

00:06:06.190 --> 00:06:08.392
Then he's guaranteed
to make a lot of money.

00:06:08.392 --> 00:06:10.600
But in the fund business,
you can find a minor league

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:12.183
where you can hit
for a better average

00:06:12.183 --> 00:06:14.249
because that's what
you're paid on."

00:06:14.249 --> 00:06:15.790
"I remember one of
our guys taking us

00:06:15.790 --> 00:06:17.990
into Korea in the early
1990s and the market

00:06:17.990 --> 00:06:19.830
was so inefficient
that it was a goldmine

00:06:19.830 --> 00:06:21.356
if you knew what you were doing.

00:06:21.356 --> 00:06:23.480
My point is that to be
successful in this business,

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:25.229
you don't have to be
better than everybody

00:06:25.229 --> 00:06:27.000
everywhere, just
better than everybody

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:28.600
in the league in which you play.

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:30.430
It's maybe today more
difficult to find

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:34.270
those inefficient areas,
but it's not impossible."

00:06:34.270 --> 00:06:37.670
So the central conceit
of any investor

00:06:37.670 --> 00:06:39.460
is that you figured
something out

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:47.050
that the market doesn't know or
the market has just got wrong.

00:06:47.050 --> 00:06:51.630
If what's priced into the stock
is just what everybody assumes

00:06:51.630 --> 00:06:53.950
and what the consensus
is, it's very unlikely

00:06:53.950 --> 00:06:56.460
that that stock is going to
be a successful investment.

00:06:56.460 --> 00:07:02.260
The price reflects the future,
as the consensus sees it.

00:07:02.260 --> 00:07:04.870
And I think that's something I
think people don't-- it's like,

00:07:04.870 --> 00:07:08.980
OK, Google is a great company,
but that doesn't always mean

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:12.010
that investing in Google
stock is a great investment.

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:16.630
It may be that the market is so
enamored with Google's future

00:07:16.630 --> 00:07:20.240
that the price you'd have to
pay it own a share of Google

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:22.580
isn't a value, and it won't
be a great investment.

00:07:22.580 --> 00:07:24.330
That doesn't mean it's
not a great company

00:07:24.330 --> 00:07:26.470
and won't still
perform extremely well,

00:07:26.470 --> 00:07:28.310
but it may not be
a great investment.

00:07:28.310 --> 00:07:31.600
So I think one
quote that captured

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:34.990
that kind of notion really
well, which is really important,

00:07:34.990 --> 00:07:36.930
was from a publisher
of "The Daily Racing

00:07:36.930 --> 00:07:38.820
Forum," of all places.

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:40.910
He said, "The issue is not
which horse in the race

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:43.780
is the most likely winner,
but which horse or horses

00:07:43.780 --> 00:07:46.350
are offering odds that
exceed their actual chances

00:07:46.350 --> 00:07:47.366
of victory.

00:07:47.366 --> 00:07:48.990
There's no such thing
as liking a horse

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:51.480
to win a race, only an
attractive discrepancy

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:55.720
between his chances
and his price."

00:07:55.720 --> 00:08:01.180
OK, so that puts a premium on
what successful investors often

00:08:01.180 --> 00:08:03.860
call the variant perception.

00:08:03.860 --> 00:08:08.450
Actually knowing what it is
or identifying what you think

00:08:08.450 --> 00:08:12.740
are the reasons a
stock is mispriced.

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:16.660
A lot of investors may just
imagine, OK, the stock is cheap

00:08:16.660 --> 00:08:20.270
and that's eventually
going to work its way out.

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:22.684
But I think what we found
is that a lot of the best

00:08:22.684 --> 00:08:24.100
investors go beyond
that, and they

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:28.210
want to understand at
least why it's cheap.

00:08:28.210 --> 00:08:29.740
Why would these be cheap?

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:32.320
What's going on that
could make this cheap?

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:36.743
And that is the
subject of this quote

00:08:36.743 --> 00:08:38.659
that I thought said it
pretty well from Curtis

00:08:38.659 --> 00:08:41.049
Macnguyen who's
at Ivory Capital.

00:08:41.049 --> 00:08:43.059
"Why something is
mispriced is too often

00:08:43.059 --> 00:08:44.640
ignored by value investors.

00:08:44.640 --> 00:08:47.140
The general thinking is that
it doesn't really matter.

00:08:47.140 --> 00:08:48.940
If you're right that
something is mispriced

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:50.820
it will eventually
take care of itself.

00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:53.890
We think it matters because
you can conceivably avoid a lot

00:08:53.890 --> 00:08:56.950
of pain waiting for truth to
prevail if you have a good read

00:08:56.950 --> 00:08:59.780
on why it currently doesn't."

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:03.270
So again, just to
reiterate a little bit,

00:09:03.270 --> 00:09:05.740
just because a company
is a good company

00:09:05.740 --> 00:09:07.490
doesn't mean it's a
good stock investment.

00:09:07.490 --> 00:09:09.990
There has to be something
about your perception

00:09:09.990 --> 00:09:12.670
of how the assets they have
or how the future's going

00:09:12.670 --> 00:09:15.090
to play out that differs from
what everybody else thinks

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:18.570
and what's built
into the stock price.

00:09:18.570 --> 00:09:21.300
So a logical question
following that would be,

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:25.124
so why do stocks get mispriced?

00:09:25.124 --> 00:09:26.040
It's efficient market.

00:09:26.040 --> 00:09:29.340
A lot of academics
will tell you that it's

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:32.550
an extremely efficient market
and you should not even

00:09:32.550 --> 00:09:34.130
try to beat the market.

00:09:34.130 --> 00:09:38.470
So what a fundamental
value investor

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:40.690
who is an active
manager is trying to do

00:09:40.690 --> 00:09:45.070
is identify what's
going on that could

00:09:45.070 --> 00:09:47.120
make this the stock cheap.

00:09:47.120 --> 00:09:50.630
And I thought that was summed
up pretty well in this quote

00:09:50.630 --> 00:09:53.030
from Steve Morrow of
New South Capital.

00:09:53.030 --> 00:09:54.850
"We believe the
market often misprices

00:09:54.850 --> 00:09:59.820
stocks due to neglect, emotion,
misinterpretation, or myopia.

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:02.600
So our value add comes from
bottom-up stock selection.

00:10:02.600 --> 00:10:04.054
We're trying to
buy at low prices

00:10:04.054 --> 00:10:06.220
relative to our current
estimate of intrinsic value,

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:09.660
and we want to believe that
intrinsic value will grow."

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:13.274
So neglect, emotion,
misinterpretation, or myopia.

00:10:13.274 --> 00:10:14.690
Those are the types
of things that

00:10:14.690 --> 00:10:17.290
can lead a stock not
to reflect accurately

00:10:17.290 --> 00:10:19.690
what's going on in the future.

00:10:19.690 --> 00:10:21.940
Howard Marks of
Oaktree Capital who

00:10:21.940 --> 00:10:26.940
is a longtime very
articulate investor

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:29.490
puts it this way in
a more general way.

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:31.830
"Investment markets follow
a pendulum-like swing

00:10:31.830 --> 00:10:34.670
between euphoria and
depression, between celebrating

00:10:34.670 --> 00:10:37.160
positive developments and
obsessing over negatives,

00:10:37.160 --> 00:10:40.130
and thus, between
overpriced and underpriced."

00:10:40.130 --> 00:10:42.860
"There are few things of which
we can be sure and this is one.

00:10:42.860 --> 00:10:45.200
Extreme market
behavior will reverse.

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:47.700
Those who believe the pendulum
will move in one direction

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:50.570
forever or reside in
an extreme forever

00:10:50.570 --> 00:10:52.650
eventually will lose huge sums.

00:10:52.650 --> 00:10:54.720
Those who understand
the pendulum's behavior

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:57.110
can benefit enormously."

00:10:57.110 --> 00:10:58.880
So what kind of
situations can lead

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:01.880
to neglect, emotion,
misinterpretation, or myopia,

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:06.010
and therefore, potentially
inaccurate stock prices?

00:11:06.010 --> 00:11:08.010
A lot of things can
make that happen,

00:11:08.010 --> 00:11:10.560
but there tends to be change.

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:12.400
There tends to be uncertainty.

00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:13.970
And quite often
there tends to be

00:11:13.970 --> 00:11:16.740
a problem or multiple problems.

00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:21.840
These are things that
can throw off or cloud

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:24.060
what the future may
hold to a greater degree

00:11:24.060 --> 00:11:28.280
than if everything's
kind of going OK.

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:31.772
Again, I'm doing this
because I think the people

00:11:31.772 --> 00:11:33.730
that we interviewed say
it better than I would,

00:11:33.730 --> 00:11:37.970
so I'm going to quote John
Jacobson from Highfields

00:11:37.970 --> 00:11:39.770
Capital where he
talks about where

00:11:39.770 --> 00:11:41.980
he looks for opportunities.

00:11:41.980 --> 00:11:46.390
So what is the fertile ground
for potential mispricing?

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:48.290
"Two kinds of events
create volatility,

00:11:48.290 --> 00:11:49.980
which creates opportunity.

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:51.900
The first revolve around
individual companies,

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:55.750
such as earnings misses,
unexpected news, M&amp;A activity,

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:58.280
restructurings, and legal
issues-- things that

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:01.770
can make prices and valuations
change relatively quickly.

00:12:01.770 --> 00:12:03.890
We want to understand
what made the price change

00:12:03.890 --> 00:12:05.639
and then figure out
whether the facts have

00:12:05.639 --> 00:12:07.440
changed as much as the price.

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:10.379
To the extent they haven't,
that can be an opportunity."

00:12:10.379 --> 00:12:11.920
"The other major
source of volatility

00:12:11.920 --> 00:12:15.410
is when a macro event or
trend causes markets to move.

00:12:15.410 --> 00:12:16.820
The market reflects
at any moment

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:20.540
what investors think
XYZ's business is worth.

00:12:20.540 --> 00:12:23.330
So if macroeconomic factors
force people to buy and sell

00:12:23.330 --> 00:12:25.910
its securities, but we believe
those factors have nothing

00:12:25.910 --> 00:12:28.160
to do with the underlying
fundamentals of the company,

00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:29.826
or less to do with
the fundamentals that

00:12:29.826 --> 00:12:31.560
is being reflected
in the share price,

00:12:31.560 --> 00:12:34.059
that can also be
an opportunity."

00:12:34.059 --> 00:12:36.350
You guys probably notice,
even looking at Google stock,

00:12:36.350 --> 00:12:39.350
if you look at a Google stock
chart over the last five years,

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:41.600
you'll see it moves.

00:12:41.600 --> 00:12:42.840
It moves quite a bit.

00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:45.970
And it moves a lot
more, one could argue,

00:12:45.970 --> 00:12:49.240
than the actual fundamental
reality of what's

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:51.100
going on at Google
at any given time.

00:12:51.100 --> 00:12:54.684
And it's that if this is what's
going on at Google at any time

00:12:54.684 --> 00:12:56.100
and this is the
stock price, there

00:12:56.100 --> 00:13:01.520
can be opportunities to buy the
stock when it's inefficiently

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:03.520
priced.

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:07.140
So while most discussions
of stocks talk about what

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:10.380
can go right about a
stock-- everybody's

00:13:10.380 --> 00:13:13.000
talking about what's the upside,
this is going to be great,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:14.624
it's going to double.

00:13:14.624 --> 00:13:16.790
One thing that I think
distinguishes value investors

00:13:16.790 --> 00:13:18.623
somewhat is that they
pay a lot of attention

00:13:18.623 --> 00:13:21.720
to what could go wrong,
what's the downside.

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:23.780
And that's well
captured in this quote

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:27.067
from Ragen Steinke of
Westwood Management.

00:13:27.067 --> 00:13:29.650
"The very first thing we do when
we start to analyze a company

00:13:29.650 --> 00:13:31.580
is to ask ourselves
how far the stock

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:33.820
price would fall
if we were wrong.

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:35.970
It's not some back of
the envelope calculation,

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:38.590
but a full assessment looking
at liquidation asset values

00:13:38.590 --> 00:13:40.860
and stressing the business
model and valuation levels

00:13:40.860 --> 00:13:43.200
under any number
of bad scenarios."

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:45.540
"If the downside is more
than 30% from today's price,

00:13:45.540 --> 00:13:47.770
it's unlikely we'll
invest, regardless

00:13:47.770 --> 00:13:48.900
of the upside potential.

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:51.730
If we can't establish a concrete
downside number, which probably

00:13:51.730 --> 00:13:54.580
means it isn't far from
100%, we absolutely

00:13:54.580 --> 00:13:56.510
won't buy the stock."

00:13:56.510 --> 00:13:58.950
"Going through this
first sets the tone

00:13:58.950 --> 00:14:00.390
we want to set in our research.

00:14:00.390 --> 00:14:02.490
Rather than start looking
to convince ourselves

00:14:02.490 --> 00:14:04.710
why we should buy
something, we start out

00:14:04.710 --> 00:14:06.530
trying to prove why
we shouldn't buy it.

00:14:06.530 --> 00:14:08.620
We try to keep that
level of skepticism

00:14:08.620 --> 00:14:10.510
alive throughout the process."

00:14:10.510 --> 00:14:13.580
I think that's a hallmark
of value investors, that

00:14:13.580 --> 00:14:16.880
kind of-- any investor
has to have some optimism.

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:18.580
You wouldn't invest
if you weren't

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:20.520
optimistic about a
company's prospects.

00:14:20.520 --> 00:14:23.210
But skepticism is
kind of a hallmark

00:14:23.210 --> 00:14:26.680
I think of a good
investor, and really

00:14:26.680 --> 00:14:29.180
thinking about what
could go wrong.

00:14:29.180 --> 00:14:30.970
It's great if a
stock could double,

00:14:30.970 --> 00:14:32.590
but if that stock
could go to zero,

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:34.100
you should think about that.

00:14:38.580 --> 00:14:40.710
So Whitney will
speak in more detail

00:14:40.710 --> 00:14:43.110
about how smart investors
go about determining

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:44.280
what a stock is worth.

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:46.320
But even if you're
able to do that well,

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:49.790
there are a lot of things that
can trip you up as an investor.

00:14:49.790 --> 00:14:53.810
And a lot of that revolves
around anything doing

00:14:53.810 --> 00:14:59.230
with money can set off all
kinds of irrational responses

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:00.630
on people's parts.

00:15:00.630 --> 00:15:04.400
It could be you're assuming
that what just happened

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:06.630
is what's going
to happen forever.

00:15:06.630 --> 00:15:10.880
Or you're panicking because
your stock went down

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:17.340
and it feels really bad to
have money evaporate like that.

00:15:17.340 --> 00:15:21.140
You could be that you're only
looking for evidence that

00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:23.820
confirms what you already
believe and you're really

00:15:23.820 --> 00:15:27.220
ignoring evidence that
disconfirms what you already

00:15:27.220 --> 00:15:27.720
believe.

00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:29.940
So these are the types of things
that can throw people off,

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:32.439
and this is the reason why it
is so hard to beat the market.

00:15:32.439 --> 00:15:36.820
People make a lot of behavioral
and emotional mistakes.

00:15:36.820 --> 00:15:39.440
And I think one
of the things that

00:15:39.440 --> 00:15:42.110
sets really good
investors apart is

00:15:42.110 --> 00:15:44.469
they're able to deal
with that pretty well,

00:15:44.469 --> 00:15:45.260
however they do it.

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:48.760
Whether it's just
innate wiring or it's

00:15:48.760 --> 00:15:50.330
they've learned
it over time, you

00:15:50.330 --> 00:15:57.100
have to control your
basest instincts somewhere.

00:15:57.100 --> 00:15:58.760
I have a couple
quotes here from two

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:02.220
very longtime, very successful
investors, one of whom

00:16:02.220 --> 00:16:04.569
is Seth Klarman of
the Baupost Group.

00:16:04.569 --> 00:16:06.360
"As Graham, Dodd and
Buffett have all said,

00:16:06.360 --> 00:16:07.470
you should always
remember that you

00:16:07.470 --> 00:16:09.200
don't have to swing
at every pitch.

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:11.780
You can wait for opportunities
that fit your criteria,

00:16:11.780 --> 00:16:14.220
and if you don't find
them, patiently wait.

00:16:14.220 --> 00:16:17.090
Deciding not to panic
is still a decision."

00:16:17.090 --> 00:16:19.450
And that's just-- I mean
everyone's probably felt it.

00:16:19.450 --> 00:16:27.080
Like if you were an investor and
you lived through 2008, 2009,

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:28.660
it feels really bad.

00:16:28.660 --> 00:16:30.940
Reading the paper was really
hard, and it feels bad.

00:16:30.940 --> 00:16:34.900
And there was a
really strong tendency

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:37.790
in those cases to
just want to get out.

00:16:37.790 --> 00:16:40.190
Make the pain go away.

00:16:40.190 --> 00:16:43.630
And that's perfectly natural.

00:16:43.630 --> 00:16:45.520
It's evolutionary
in a lot of ways,

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:50.670
but it's not the greatest
thing to do as an investor.

00:16:50.670 --> 00:16:54.560
The person who panicked
and sold in March of 2009

00:16:54.560 --> 00:16:57.400
and then was so scared
that they haven't

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:02.250
gone in for the last five years,
they've left a lot of money

00:17:02.250 --> 00:17:05.170
on the table and
that's a big mistake.

00:17:05.170 --> 00:17:07.260
This is another
quote from a guy who

00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:08.800
is a very longtime investor.

00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:11.886
He's in his 70s and he
still really does well,

00:17:11.886 --> 00:17:13.260
and he just very
matter of factly

00:17:13.260 --> 00:17:16.516
said, "I honestly don't feel any
of the emotional ups and downs

00:17:16.516 --> 00:17:18.099
from the market's
day to day activity.

00:17:18.099 --> 00:17:20.119
I just don't worry about
short-term volatility."

00:17:20.119 --> 00:17:21.910
I think that's something
as an investor you

00:17:21.910 --> 00:17:23.980
have to learn how to deal with.

00:17:27.430 --> 00:17:30.940
I guess my last thought is
just one about humility.

00:17:30.940 --> 00:17:35.880
There's no question that
confidence and conviction

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:40.450
are essential elements
to being a good investor.

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:44.060
But as we say in the book,
like pepperoni pizza and fine

00:17:44.060 --> 00:17:48.930
scotch, too much of a good
thing can cause problems.

00:17:48.930 --> 00:17:51.660
So the message is
not to ever think

00:17:51.660 --> 00:17:54.066
you've got it all figured
out as an investor,

00:17:54.066 --> 00:17:55.440
and that's probably
true in life.

00:17:55.440 --> 00:17:59.530
But don't assume you've got it,
you've got this thing nailed,

00:17:59.530 --> 00:18:04.330
because the market will
inevitably humble you.

00:18:04.330 --> 00:18:07.950
So here's a quote from
Kyle Bass on that.

00:18:07.950 --> 00:18:09.920
"You obviously need to
develop strong opinions

00:18:09.920 --> 00:18:11.710
and to have the conviction
to stick with them when

00:18:11.710 --> 00:18:13.959
you believe you're right,
even when everybody else may

00:18:13.959 --> 00:18:15.037
think you're an idiot.

00:18:15.037 --> 00:18:16.620
But where I've seen
ego get in the way

00:18:16.620 --> 00:18:18.730
is by not always being
open to questions

00:18:18.730 --> 00:18:20.979
and to input that
could change your mind.

00:18:20.979 --> 00:18:22.520
If you can't ever
admit you're wrong,

00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:24.311
you're more likely to
hang onto your losers

00:18:24.311 --> 00:18:28.840
and sell your winners, which
is not a recipe for success."

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:30.950
So I'm going to turn
it now over to Whitney

00:18:30.950 --> 00:18:33.630
who will try to shed some light
on whether Google stock is

00:18:33.630 --> 00:18:35.812
worth owning today.

00:18:35.812 --> 00:18:37.520
WHITNEY TILSON: Good
afternoon, everyone.

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:38.590
Thanks for joining us.

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:43.410
So let's talk about Google.

00:18:43.410 --> 00:18:47.020
And I have a history
here with Google.

00:18:47.020 --> 00:18:51.540
And before I show it--
and I run a hedge fund.

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:53.470
Started-- this is my 16th year.

00:18:53.470 --> 00:18:56.840
This is my track record
after my usurious fees, net

00:18:56.840 --> 00:18:58.220
to investors.

00:18:58.220 --> 00:19:01.880
And the only reason I show it is
I'm not here promoting my fund,

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:05.150
but rather I'm going to show
you how spectacularly wrong

00:19:05.150 --> 00:19:07.380
I can be.

00:19:07.380 --> 00:19:11.460
And I just want you to not
think I'm the world's stupidest

00:19:11.460 --> 00:19:12.820
investor.

00:19:12.820 --> 00:19:16.730
So very, very few investors
beat the market over time,

00:19:16.730 --> 00:19:18.781
and so I think it's
a good track record.

00:19:18.781 --> 00:19:20.280
It's not a spectacular
track record,

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:21.620
but it's a good track record.

00:19:21.620 --> 00:19:23.050
Very few managers
beat the market

00:19:23.050 --> 00:19:24.174
over a long period of time.

00:19:24.174 --> 00:19:27.210
I've done so, despite every
once in a while making

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:28.520
a spectacularly bad call.

00:19:28.520 --> 00:19:31.547
So a little over 10
years ago in an article

00:19:31.547 --> 00:19:33.630
I wrote for The Motley
Fool called "The Tech Stock

00:19:33.630 --> 00:19:37.440
Opportunity," I wrote actually
something reasonably smart

00:19:37.440 --> 00:19:40.820
here initially that I think
the tech sector offers

00:19:40.820 --> 00:19:42.530
fertile ground for
value investors.

00:19:42.530 --> 00:19:45.750
A lot of great companies
growing rapidly,

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:49.440
strong balance sheets,
and very importantly,

00:19:49.440 --> 00:19:51.350
a lot of crazy investors.

00:19:51.350 --> 00:19:53.590
If you are a sound
and rational investor,

00:19:53.590 --> 00:19:55.500
you want to go to
places, you want

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:58.190
to compete with
irrational people.

00:19:58.190 --> 00:20:01.425
Because a company misses
an earnings estimate

00:20:01.425 --> 00:20:04.660
and they drop the stock 50%,
when the value of the company

00:20:04.660 --> 00:20:07.270
has not changed by
50% in all likelihood.

00:20:07.270 --> 00:20:09.590
Similarly, you want
to buy something

00:20:09.590 --> 00:20:12.559
where the stock might rise
back to intrinsic value,

00:20:12.559 --> 00:20:14.850
but then investors get euphoric
and give you the chance

00:20:14.850 --> 00:20:16.860
to hang on, and it'll
trade at double or triple

00:20:16.860 --> 00:20:18.077
or quadruple intrinsic value.

00:20:18.077 --> 00:20:19.910
That's where you really
make a lot of money.

00:20:19.910 --> 00:20:22.800
So that's what I was
pointing out here.

00:20:22.800 --> 00:20:26.410
But then I digressed
in this article

00:20:26.410 --> 00:20:30.610
to a company that had recently
gone public named Google.

00:20:30.610 --> 00:20:33.920
And this is what I
wrote about Google.

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:36.559
I said, "There's a huge
difference between Dell

00:20:36.559 --> 00:20:38.600
and Google, both are lumped
into the tech sector.

00:20:38.600 --> 00:20:41.320
I'd argue that Dell is primarily
a manufacturing, assembling,

00:20:41.320 --> 00:20:43.760
sales and service business,
not a technology company.

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:45.635
Dell doesn't care which
hardware and software

00:20:45.635 --> 00:20:47.850
products wins the
technology wars.

00:20:47.850 --> 00:20:49.922
It simply buys, assembles,
and sells and supports

00:20:49.922 --> 00:20:51.130
whatever its customers want."

00:20:51.130 --> 00:20:54.100
"So in short, I think the odds
are very high, say 80% to 90%

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:56.750
that Dell is a major computer
company in 20 years."

00:20:56.750 --> 00:20:59.922
And that actually has
been proven right I think.

00:20:59.922 --> 00:21:02.130
And by the way, I wasn't
recommending the Dell stock,

00:21:02.130 --> 00:21:04.130
which was very
overvalued at the time,

00:21:04.130 --> 00:21:06.180
and that was correct as well.

00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:08.980
However, then,
eating crow, I said,

00:21:08.980 --> 00:21:10.990
"Google, in contrast,
more typical tech company,

00:21:10.990 --> 00:21:13.140
one that must invest heavily
to remain on the cutting

00:21:13.140 --> 00:21:14.840
edge or its customers
will quickly and easily

00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:15.840
flock to competitors.

00:21:15.840 --> 00:21:17.100
Just as Google
came out of nowhere

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:19.350
to unseat Yahoo as the leading
search engine, so might

00:21:19.350 --> 00:21:20.940
another company
do this to Google.

00:21:20.940 --> 00:21:23.537
I admire Google and what
it has accomplished,

00:21:23.537 --> 00:21:25.870
and I'm a happy user, but I'm
quite certain that there's

00:21:25.870 --> 00:21:29.280
only a fairly shallow, narrow
moat around its business."

00:21:29.280 --> 00:21:32.240
Making it worse,
I then continued.

00:21:32.240 --> 00:21:32.986
"Think about it.

00:21:32.986 --> 00:21:35.110
What are the odds that
Google is the leading search

00:21:35.110 --> 00:21:37.210
engine in five years,
much less 20 years?

00:21:37.210 --> 00:21:40.120
50-50 at best I
suspect, and I'd wager

00:21:40.120 --> 00:21:42.990
that odds are at least 90% that
its profit margins and growth

00:21:42.990 --> 00:21:45.510
rate will be materially
lower five years from now.

00:21:45.510 --> 00:21:47.980
Yet investors appear ready
to value this company

00:21:47.980 --> 00:21:49.480
as much as $36 billion."

00:21:49.480 --> 00:21:51.950
I guess this was on
the eve of the IPO.

00:21:51.950 --> 00:21:54.350
"Nearly 200 times
trailing earnings.

00:21:54.350 --> 00:21:56.070
And by the way, about
12 times revenues."

00:21:56.070 --> 00:21:59.620
Google at the time had about
three billion in revenues.

00:21:59.620 --> 00:22:00.959
"Ha!

00:22:00.959 --> 00:22:03.500
Google with the same market cap
as McDonald's, a stock I own?

00:22:03.500 --> 00:22:03.810
Ha!

00:22:03.810 --> 00:22:05.785
I believe it is virtually
certain that Google stock will

00:22:05.785 --> 00:22:07.710
be highly disappointing to
investors foolish enough

00:22:07.710 --> 00:22:09.460
to participate in its
over-hyped offering.

00:22:09.460 --> 00:22:12.844
You can hold me to that."

00:22:12.844 --> 00:22:14.760
Remember John was just
talking about humility?

00:22:14.760 --> 00:22:16.920
This is a business
that keeps you humble.

00:22:16.920 --> 00:22:20.930
So by the way, the
margins actually

00:22:20.930 --> 00:22:24.380
have sort of been stable, maybe
even declined a little bit,

00:22:24.380 --> 00:22:26.850
so I wasn't completely
wrong that margins

00:22:26.850 --> 00:22:29.990
would come under
pressure over time.

00:22:29.990 --> 00:22:33.290
But where I was spectacularly
wrong was the growth.

00:22:33.290 --> 00:22:37.560
Revenue has gone up more than
20x in the last 10 years.

00:22:37.560 --> 00:22:41.010
It's been one of the most
spectacular growth success

00:22:41.010 --> 00:22:43.160
stories over time.

00:22:43.160 --> 00:22:45.850
So if you can go
to the next slide.

00:22:49.110 --> 00:22:51.840
And that has translated with
a little decline in margins,

00:22:51.840 --> 00:22:53.950
but basically that growth
has fallen straight

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:58.020
to the bottom line, and earnings
from continuing operations

00:22:58.020 --> 00:23:00.400
have gone up to
over $12 billion.

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:05.350
That's translated into
earnings per share, excluding

00:23:05.350 --> 00:23:08.320
extra items, of
almost $20 a share.

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:11.190
So not surprisingly,
the stock has followed.

00:23:11.190 --> 00:23:13.780
Stocks over time tend
to follow the earnings,

00:23:13.780 --> 00:23:16.330
and the stock has been
approximately more

00:23:16.330 --> 00:23:20.640
than a 10-bagger since I
said it was wildly overvalued

00:23:20.640 --> 00:23:22.640
and should be
avoided at all costs.

00:23:22.640 --> 00:23:24.710
So what did I miss?

00:23:24.710 --> 00:23:26.260
And by the way,
just as a general,

00:23:26.260 --> 00:23:28.380
there are a lot of
companies out there today,

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:32.450
small companies, three
billion in revenues trading

00:23:32.450 --> 00:23:37.570
at 12 times revenues
and 200 times earnings.

00:23:37.570 --> 00:23:41.890
Salesforce.com has about four
billion in revenues or so,

00:23:41.890 --> 00:23:44.330
trending toward five and
1/2 over the next year.

00:23:44.330 --> 00:23:45.800
Trades about eight
times revenues,

00:23:45.800 --> 00:23:49.920
120 times next year's earnings.

00:23:49.920 --> 00:23:51.420
And so investors
are sort of betting

00:23:51.420 --> 00:23:54.240
that that's going to look like
Google over the next 10 years

00:23:54.240 --> 00:23:56.890
or so, and I think the odds
of that are extremely low.

00:23:56.890 --> 00:23:59.770
In general, you guys
are the outlier.

00:23:59.770 --> 00:24:02.860
As a general rule, 99
out of 100 companies

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:04.770
that grade at such
extreme valuations

00:24:04.770 --> 00:24:07.610
turn out to be lousy, if not
catastrophic investments.

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:10.490
So I'm not convinced
I was necessarily

00:24:10.490 --> 00:24:14.890
wrong to say a prudent value
investor should probably not

00:24:14.890 --> 00:24:19.990
speculate in a very hyped IPO.

00:24:19.990 --> 00:24:22.970
Statistically speaking, it was
probably pretty sound advice.

00:24:22.970 --> 00:24:24.700
But you guys were the outlier.

00:24:24.700 --> 00:24:27.820
You guys were the one in
100 that did pull it off.

00:24:27.820 --> 00:24:29.340
So what did I miss?

00:24:29.340 --> 00:24:30.780
I missed Google's moat.

00:24:30.780 --> 00:24:34.660
It seemed to me that anyone
could just easily switch,

00:24:34.660 --> 00:24:35.400
and so forth.

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:38.070
And theoretically,
someone easily could.

00:24:38.070 --> 00:24:40.245
But on the other hand,
people get into habits,

00:24:40.245 --> 00:24:42.620
tend to be very sticky, and
if you have a better product,

00:24:42.620 --> 00:24:45.161
you're constantly innovating,
stay ahead of your competitors,

00:24:45.161 --> 00:24:46.500
that moat can build over time.

00:24:46.500 --> 00:24:49.800
And I missed the very powerful
virtuous cycle at work

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:50.700
with Google.

00:24:50.700 --> 00:24:53.520
A large user base translates
into large advertiser base,

00:24:53.520 --> 00:24:55.590
better monetization,
more R&amp;D dollars,

00:24:55.590 --> 00:24:58.940
yielding a better product,
which a better product is

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:01.080
a high barrier to entry,
which then attracts

00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:03.310
more of a user base, et cetera.

00:25:03.310 --> 00:25:06.280
By the way, I made nine times
my money in the last two years

00:25:06.280 --> 00:25:07.050
on Netflix.

00:25:07.050 --> 00:25:08.561
I was initially at
one time shorted.

00:25:08.561 --> 00:25:10.560
And by the way, at least
I was not stupid enough

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:11.360
to short Google.

00:25:11.360 --> 00:25:13.280
OK, so I've never lost
any money on Google.

00:25:13.280 --> 00:25:15.750
I just haven't made
any money on it.

00:25:15.750 --> 00:25:18.650
Netflix I was dumb
enough to short

00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:21.335
because I thought anyone
can stream movies, whatever.

00:25:21.335 --> 00:25:23.430
And then I came to
realize, Netflix

00:25:23.430 --> 00:25:25.330
has a similar
virtuous cycle going

00:25:25.330 --> 00:25:27.760
on where they have
80% of the streaming

00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:28.760
customers in the world.

00:25:28.760 --> 00:25:31.920
They then take all that
revenue and buy great content,

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:34.780
which then attracts
80% to 90% to 100%

00:25:34.780 --> 00:25:37.510
of every incremental new
streaming customer on earth

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:41.090
is joining Netflix, which they
can reinvest in better content.

00:25:41.090 --> 00:25:43.215
And the price of
admission now, Netflix

00:25:43.215 --> 00:25:45.760
is spending over $3
billion a year on content.

00:25:45.760 --> 00:25:48.780
The price of admission
is now very, very high.

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:51.057
Even if a much bigger
company-- a Google.

00:25:51.057 --> 00:25:52.140
Amazon is trying to do it.

00:25:52.140 --> 00:25:53.890
If Google wanted
to try and do it,

00:25:53.890 --> 00:25:56.430
it's now going to cost billions
and billions of dollars.

00:25:56.430 --> 00:25:59.040
And from a company that's
generating no revenue,

00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:01.150
to even open your doors
and start a service,

00:26:01.150 --> 00:26:04.290
you've got to license $3
billion worth of content.

00:26:04.290 --> 00:26:06.640
Whereas Netflix has
50 million paying

00:26:06.640 --> 00:26:08.880
subscribers paying
for that content.

00:26:08.880 --> 00:26:12.650
So Netflix I thought
was a commodity business

00:26:12.650 --> 00:26:14.720
is looking like a
winner-take-all business.

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:16.510
You guys looked like
a commodity business,

00:26:16.510 --> 00:26:18.340
and I think in
many of your areas

00:26:18.340 --> 00:26:20.090
you are a winner take
all business because

00:26:20.090 --> 00:26:22.024
of this kind of virtuous cycle.

00:26:22.024 --> 00:26:23.690
It's very, very
powerful and something I

00:26:23.690 --> 00:26:25.620
didn't appreciate 10 years ago.

00:26:25.620 --> 00:26:27.530
I appreciate it more today.

00:26:27.530 --> 00:26:30.192
So let's talk about
the stock today.

00:26:30.192 --> 00:26:31.150
It's a couple days old.

00:26:31.150 --> 00:26:34.310
It closed today, its right
around 5.37 right now.

00:26:34.310 --> 00:26:36.092
$368 billion market cap.

00:26:36.092 --> 00:26:37.800
You've got a ton of
cash, sliver of debt,

00:26:37.800 --> 00:26:41.010
$316 billion enterprise.

00:26:41.010 --> 00:26:44.380
Like most tech companies,
a large expense

00:26:44.380 --> 00:26:46.380
is stock-based compensation.

00:26:46.380 --> 00:26:48.680
Accounting rules
require you to expense

00:26:48.680 --> 00:26:51.350
that as if it were cash,
but it is a non-cash charge.

00:26:51.350 --> 00:26:54.760
So Google, like a lot of
tech companies, analysts,

00:26:54.760 --> 00:26:58.510
they report earnings excluding
the stock-based comp.

00:26:58.510 --> 00:27:02.320
I tend to figure I don't care if
a company pays cash or dilutes

00:27:02.320 --> 00:27:04.870
me via options that are worth
a certain amount of cash.

00:27:04.870 --> 00:27:07.130
So I tend to be
pretty conservative.

00:27:07.130 --> 00:27:09.630
But these numbers will be
lower, about $5 a share

00:27:09.630 --> 00:27:11.700
lower than the earnings
per share numbers

00:27:11.700 --> 00:27:15.150
that you might see, because
about $5 a share of earnings

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:18.190
are in non-cash, you guys are
partially paid in options.

00:27:18.190 --> 00:27:22.190
So reasonable people
can disagree about that.

00:27:22.190 --> 00:27:27.160
If you want to x that out
and use EBITDA number.

00:27:27.160 --> 00:27:32.230
So Google's trading right now
at about 26 and 1/2 times this

00:27:32.230 --> 00:27:35.840
year's priced earnings,
multiple, 21 times next year's.

00:27:35.840 --> 00:27:36.690
Those multiples.

00:27:36.690 --> 00:27:38.360
That would come
down by a few points

00:27:38.360 --> 00:27:41.890
if you exclude stock-based
comp, which most analysts do.

00:27:41.890 --> 00:27:45.650
And then EBITDA numbers,
multiples as well.

00:27:45.650 --> 00:27:48.530
So what is it saying
is we're in the market

00:27:48.530 --> 00:27:52.360
probably 16 times
earnings for the S&amp;P 500.

00:27:52.360 --> 00:27:53.860
So any way you could
it you guys are

00:27:53.860 --> 00:27:57.120
at some premium to that,
but not a crazy premium.

00:27:57.120 --> 00:27:59.250
But you guys are growing
your revenues 20% a year.

00:27:59.250 --> 00:28:02.620
Average S&amp;P company's growing
their revenues maybe 5% a year.

00:28:02.620 --> 00:28:05.390
So you guys have
massively higher margins,

00:28:05.390 --> 00:28:07.000
returns on capital, et cetera.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:10.770
So it's a far superior
company trading

00:28:10.770 --> 00:28:15.600
at a premium price, but
not a crazy premium price.

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:17.910
So that's sort of interesting.

00:28:17.910 --> 00:28:20.710
I typically like buying out
of favor companies where

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:22.300
a sentiment is
extremely negative,

00:28:22.300 --> 00:28:24.770
stocks near a 52-week
low, et cetera.

00:28:24.770 --> 00:28:26.770
Sort of betting on a
stabilization and/or

00:28:26.770 --> 00:28:27.370
turnaround.

00:28:27.370 --> 00:28:29.730
That's typically what I do.

00:28:29.730 --> 00:28:32.210
But every once in a
while-- I bought Netflix

00:28:32.210 --> 00:28:37.130
after it crashed from 300
down to around $50 a share.

00:28:37.130 --> 00:28:39.550
When I thought, look, they
can't fix the business.

00:28:39.550 --> 00:28:42.630
Somebody should buy
them for $3 billion.

00:28:42.630 --> 00:28:44.650
I think, by the
way, Google has made

00:28:44.650 --> 00:28:47.861
a number of very savvy
acquisitions over the years.

00:28:47.861 --> 00:28:49.860
Somebody should be kicking
themselves at Google.

00:28:49.860 --> 00:28:54.050
You didn't buy Netflix when it
had a $3.2 billion market cap.

00:28:54.050 --> 00:28:55.460
It was a great business.

00:28:55.460 --> 00:28:56.430
It is a great business.

00:28:56.430 --> 00:29:02.070
So I'm actually sort of
intrigued with Google.

00:29:02.070 --> 00:29:04.109
The other thing,
by the way, is it's

00:29:04.109 --> 00:29:05.900
such a big company with
such a large market

00:29:05.900 --> 00:29:08.630
cap it's hard to make a
lot of money buying things

00:29:08.630 --> 00:29:10.440
with multi-hundred
billion market caps.

00:29:10.440 --> 00:29:12.970
I mean just size is
sort of an anchor.

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:14.630
I run a pretty small fund.

00:29:14.630 --> 00:29:16.900
I tend to look for
smaller companies.

00:29:16.900 --> 00:29:20.630
But it's pretty interesting.

00:29:20.630 --> 00:29:21.920
I'm intrigued by Google.

00:29:21.920 --> 00:29:24.020
I'm going to do some
more work on it.

00:29:24.020 --> 00:29:26.462
So let's just talk about
last quarter's earnings.

00:29:26.462 --> 00:29:28.170
You guys have probably
already seen this,

00:29:28.170 --> 00:29:30.030
but revenues grew 20%.

00:29:30.030 --> 00:29:31.790
Margins got squeezed.

00:29:31.790 --> 00:29:33.780
Expenses rose a little
faster than revenues,

00:29:33.780 --> 00:29:35.600
which squeezed margins.

00:29:35.600 --> 00:29:37.880
Depending on whether
you want to look

00:29:37.880 --> 00:29:40.480
at non-GAAP or GAAP
earnings, earnings either

00:29:40.480 --> 00:29:41.849
went up or down a little bit.

00:29:41.849 --> 00:29:43.390
But the real questions
to think about

00:29:43.390 --> 00:29:46.070
is can the company
continue to grow

00:29:46.070 --> 00:29:48.610
at least sort of
high teens, 20% rate,

00:29:48.610 --> 00:29:51.210
and will those margins
at least stabilize?

00:29:51.210 --> 00:29:55.090
And when you think about
Google, by the way, if Google

00:29:55.090 --> 00:29:58.540
were to separate
itself out and spin off

00:29:58.540 --> 00:30:01.520
Google Fiber and the
self-driving car stuff,

00:30:01.520 --> 00:30:04.110
like Google is-- a
lot of those expenses

00:30:04.110 --> 00:30:06.945
are investing in things that
are currently not generating

00:30:06.945 --> 00:30:07.445
any revenue.

00:30:07.445 --> 00:30:09.480
It's just straight out losses.

00:30:09.480 --> 00:30:11.540
Like actually, I
think a reasonable way

00:30:11.540 --> 00:30:14.860
to think about Google would
be to sort of take out

00:30:14.860 --> 00:30:18.982
all the money losing stuff
where-- these pie in the sky

00:30:18.982 --> 00:30:21.440
things-- where Google actually
has a pretty darn good track

00:30:21.440 --> 00:30:24.880
record of developing really
valuable things down the road.

00:30:24.880 --> 00:30:27.020
And I might give
Google credit for that

00:30:27.020 --> 00:30:30.380
and say, how much is their
core business really earning,

00:30:30.380 --> 00:30:31.920
x-ing out all these expenses.

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:35.499
And it might be quite
a bit of expenses,

00:30:35.499 --> 00:30:37.540
and you might actually
say Google's core business

00:30:37.540 --> 00:30:39.910
trading for 15 times earnings
or something like a market

00:30:39.910 --> 00:30:42.770
multiple, and then you're
getting a free call option

00:30:42.770 --> 00:30:44.790
on stuff that--
self-driving cars.

00:30:44.790 --> 00:30:46.990
If you guys nail that, that
could change the world.

00:30:46.990 --> 00:30:52.152
That's a worldwide game changer,
and you guys will own it.

00:30:52.152 --> 00:30:54.360
I'm not sure I'd give
Microsoft much credit for that.

00:30:54.360 --> 00:30:56.660
They have a horrible track
record of just pissing money

00:30:56.660 --> 00:31:00.190
away over the years, and
projects and acquisitions

00:31:00.190 --> 00:31:01.670
that just create no value.

00:31:01.670 --> 00:31:05.240
And Microsoft shareholders
are sort of rebelling.

00:31:05.240 --> 00:31:08.910
But you guys seem to be
a lot better at that.

00:31:08.910 --> 00:31:11.480
So again, that would
be the argument

00:31:11.480 --> 00:31:14.850
for owning Google stock
is is that it's really not

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:18.500
as expensive as it appears
because they're expensing--

00:31:18.500 --> 00:31:20.460
a lot of their expenses,
their core business

00:31:20.460 --> 00:31:23.950
is actually even much more
profitable than it appears.

00:31:23.950 --> 00:31:25.850
One of the world's
greatest businesses.

00:31:25.850 --> 00:31:29.400
And then they're investing
in a lot of new stuff

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:30.900
where there's
likelihood to pay off.

00:31:30.900 --> 00:31:33.025
So this gives you a sense--
by the way, again, what

00:31:33.025 --> 00:31:36.340
I sort of missed is is companies
that have a lot of optionality

00:31:36.340 --> 00:31:39.087
to get into new businesses,
make acquisitions, et cetera.

00:31:39.087 --> 00:31:40.670
So this was the three
billion revenues

00:31:40.670 --> 00:31:42.790
when I was disparaging
the company.

00:31:42.790 --> 00:31:46.510
And the core business grew 10x.

00:31:46.510 --> 00:31:50.080
But then stuff that didn't
even exist back then

00:31:50.080 --> 00:31:54.890
doubled to 20x revenue growth.

00:31:54.890 --> 00:31:57.490
So this is cool, right?

00:31:57.490 --> 00:32:00.160
And if you think this kind
of thing can continue,

00:32:00.160 --> 00:32:03.480
things that don't exist, don't
generate a dollar of revenue

00:32:03.480 --> 00:32:06.040
today, like Google Fiber,
self-driving cars or whatever,

00:32:06.040 --> 00:32:09.700
and that this kind of
thing continues again,

00:32:09.700 --> 00:32:12.220
this stock may look
really cheap today

00:32:12.220 --> 00:32:16.610
if you can develop some amazing
stuff and start to monetize it.

00:32:16.610 --> 00:32:19.110
So I think this
is the last slide

00:32:19.110 --> 00:32:22.900
and then we can do Q&amp;A,
which is if you make

00:32:22.900 --> 00:32:26.980
a case for the stock today is
look at the pieces overall.

00:32:26.980 --> 00:32:28.980
You continue to grow
your revenues 20%

00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:34.340
for the next four years, if
your margins just stay flat,

00:32:34.340 --> 00:32:37.820
that means the earnings
go up 20% a year.

00:32:37.820 --> 00:32:39.720
That's a double in four years.

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:43.910
A 20 multiple or so, if you
can continue to grow at 20%

00:32:43.910 --> 00:32:45.841
is a reasonable thing to assume.

00:32:45.841 --> 00:32:48.340
Might go up, might go down, but
that's actually probably not

00:32:48.340 --> 00:32:48.881
unreasonable.

00:32:48.881 --> 00:32:51.980
And therefore, the stock just
follows that same trajectory.

00:32:51.980 --> 00:32:56.060
And making 20% compounded
over the next four years

00:32:56.060 --> 00:32:59.170
isn't spectacular, but
it's pretty darn good.

00:32:59.170 --> 00:33:03.000
If I thought this
stock was very likely,

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:06.220
with low risk of downside,
very likely to be a double

00:33:06.220 --> 00:33:08.900
in four years, I don't know
all day, on a real high quality

00:33:08.900 --> 00:33:11.360
company where I think I can
double my money in for years.

00:33:11.360 --> 00:33:15.000
So that's sort of what I'll be
digging into because there are

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:19.890
very few companies this size
that can grow at that rate.

00:33:19.890 --> 00:33:24.870
Already at $66 billion, already
at a $300+ billion market cap

00:33:24.870 --> 00:33:27.640
that can double again
from there in four years.

00:33:27.640 --> 00:33:30.340
That's pretty rare, but you
guys have been doing it.

00:33:30.340 --> 00:33:33.000
So I certainly wouldn't
bet against it.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:36.370
The question is is for a
guy who only owns 15 stocks,

00:33:36.370 --> 00:33:37.920
is this one of
the best 15 stocks

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:40.050
in the universe I can find?

00:33:40.050 --> 00:33:42.040
That's the real question.

00:33:42.040 --> 00:33:44.220
So with that, do you
want to come up, John.

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:46.276
We're happy to take questions.

00:33:46.276 --> 00:33:49.400
AUDIENCE: I'd like to ask you
how to learn from mistakes.

00:33:49.400 --> 00:33:54.060
So you said that Google
was one of your mistakes,

00:33:54.060 --> 00:33:58.200
but you also said that it's
like buying a lottery ticket.

00:33:58.200 --> 00:34:01.060
Like even if you
win the lottery,

00:34:01.060 --> 00:34:03.290
it doesn't mean that it was
a right decision to make.

00:34:03.290 --> 00:34:07.340
So I just want to ask if
you make a wrong decision,

00:34:07.340 --> 00:34:09.110
do you learn from it,
or do you say, OK,

00:34:09.110 --> 00:34:11.030
this is just how it happens?

00:34:11.030 --> 00:34:12.159
WHITNEY TILSON: Yeah.

00:34:12.159 --> 00:34:12.670
It's hard.

00:34:12.670 --> 00:34:16.150
In the investing world-- the
analogy I would give you is

00:34:16.150 --> 00:34:18.639
is if you walk through
a dynamite factory

00:34:18.639 --> 00:34:22.409
with an open torch, and you
get through to the other side

00:34:22.409 --> 00:34:25.505
safely, was it a good idea?

00:34:25.505 --> 00:34:26.796
And the answer's of course not.

00:34:26.796 --> 00:34:28.587
It was an idiotic thing
to do, and the fact

00:34:28.587 --> 00:34:31.392
that you didn't die
was just good luck.

00:34:31.392 --> 00:34:32.850
But you should
never do that again.

00:34:32.850 --> 00:34:34.350
So the investing
world has-- you can

00:34:34.350 --> 00:34:37.190
learn a lot of false lessons
in the investing world.

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:40.610
You can totally screw up
the analysis and make money,

00:34:40.610 --> 00:34:43.139
and by the way, can do good
analysis and lose money, right?

00:34:43.139 --> 00:34:47.329
So learning from mistakes isn't
as simple as simply saying,

00:34:47.329 --> 00:34:48.870
well, did I make
money or lose money,

00:34:48.870 --> 00:34:54.800
because the goal of investing is
to make high probability bets.

00:34:54.800 --> 00:34:56.520
But even the highest
probability bets

00:34:56.520 --> 00:34:58.640
sometimes work against you.

00:34:58.640 --> 00:35:03.590
So the lessons-- but here,
I do think one of things

00:35:03.590 --> 00:35:07.010
I've learned, like I was
trained as a traditional value

00:35:07.010 --> 00:35:09.460
investor in the Warren
Buffett kind of school.

00:35:09.460 --> 00:35:12.570
You don't look at tech
stocks, et cetera, et cetera.

00:35:12.570 --> 00:35:17.040
And I was trained to think
about the competitive moats

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:21.920
of companies-- Coke's brand
or Costco's low cost service

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:22.790
or whatever.

00:35:22.790 --> 00:35:25.850
And what's happened
in the last 10 years,

00:35:25.850 --> 00:35:28.840
the kind of companies that
have been created that

00:35:28.840 --> 00:35:30.700
are almost like
virtual companies, that

00:35:30.700 --> 00:35:34.040
can grow very rapidly to
become global companies

00:35:34.040 --> 00:35:35.880
with enormously
high profit margins

00:35:35.880 --> 00:35:39.220
without the need to invest
incremental capital.

00:35:39.220 --> 00:35:42.360
So you guys can grow to
countries all over the world

00:35:42.360 --> 00:35:44.450
and you don't have
to manufacture stuff,

00:35:44.450 --> 00:35:47.160
you don't have to ship
it, you have no inventory.

00:35:47.160 --> 00:35:53.480
These are light business models
that create returns on capital

00:35:53.480 --> 00:35:57.860
at a rate and a scale and
a scope, a global scope,

00:35:57.860 --> 00:36:00.990
and a speed that has
never existed in history.

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:03.190
And it really requires you
to-- you can either just

00:36:03.190 --> 00:36:04.690
say-- you can be
like Warren Buffett

00:36:04.690 --> 00:36:06.170
and just say I don't
understand any of this

00:36:06.170 --> 00:36:07.030
and I'm just going to stay away.

00:36:07.030 --> 00:36:09.870
I'm not going to short it, not
going to long it, go long it.

00:36:09.870 --> 00:36:11.450
I want to understand
it because I

00:36:11.450 --> 00:36:13.850
plan to be investing
for another 50 years.

00:36:13.850 --> 00:36:18.150
And so the real learning
here, from getting my head

00:36:18.150 --> 00:36:20.600
handed to me, being short
Netflix before finally

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:22.860
appreciating it and making
nine times my money.

00:36:22.860 --> 00:36:23.610
I flipped around.

00:36:23.610 --> 00:36:25.440
So in other words, my
learning from getting

00:36:25.440 --> 00:36:28.885
killed on the short side is I
went and did a lot more work.

00:36:28.885 --> 00:36:33.200
And losing millions of
dollars focuses the mind.

00:36:33.200 --> 00:36:35.150
So losing millions
of dollars forced

00:36:35.150 --> 00:36:37.899
me to rethink what
I was missing here.

00:36:37.899 --> 00:36:39.690
Now sometimes you're
not missing something.

00:36:39.690 --> 00:36:42.190
Sometimes a short runs against
you and you're absolutely right

00:36:42.190 --> 00:36:43.380
and you've just
got to be patient

00:36:43.380 --> 00:36:45.921
and your thesis will eventually
play out, because being early

00:36:45.921 --> 00:36:49.340
and being wrong look the same,
either long or short, right?

00:36:49.340 --> 00:36:50.900
But in the case
of Netflix, you've

00:36:50.900 --> 00:36:55.980
got to keep an open mind,
and I did keep an open mind

00:36:55.980 --> 00:36:59.154
in this case, developed a
much greater appreciation

00:36:59.154 --> 00:36:59.820
for the company.

00:36:59.820 --> 00:37:02.540
So when I covered-- I've
short it from 80 to 200.

00:37:02.540 --> 00:37:03.520
I covered my short.

00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:04.550
It went to 300.

00:37:04.550 --> 00:37:05.600
I felt pretty smart.

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:08.410
Then it felt eventually to 50.

00:37:08.410 --> 00:37:10.735
It fell 80% in a matter
of about three months.

00:37:10.735 --> 00:37:12.610
And I want to kill
myself, because everything

00:37:12.610 --> 00:37:14.719
I predicted in my
short thesis came true.

00:37:14.719 --> 00:37:16.010
And I said, Whitney, you idiot.

00:37:16.010 --> 00:37:18.980
My learning was is don't
get scared out of a short.

00:37:18.980 --> 00:37:20.500
You have conviction
in it, right?

00:37:20.500 --> 00:37:22.410
But that actually
wasn't the right

00:37:22.410 --> 00:37:24.200
learning, though,
because Netflix

00:37:24.200 --> 00:37:26.840
was a massively better
company than I thought.

00:37:26.840 --> 00:37:28.820
And the key pillars
of my short thesis

00:37:28.820 --> 00:37:30.528
were there's no moat
around the business,

00:37:30.528 --> 00:37:32.822
and sort of wacky
management, and competitors

00:37:32.822 --> 00:37:34.530
are going to come in
and eat their lunch.

00:37:34.530 --> 00:37:36.630
All of my pillars of my
short thesis were wrong.

00:37:36.630 --> 00:37:39.190
I was right to cover, no matter
what happened to the stock.

00:37:39.190 --> 00:37:42.800
But what it did is is by gaining
appreciation of the company,

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:46.390
I was ready to pounce
when the stock collapsed.

00:37:46.390 --> 00:37:49.820
And so that's a great example.

00:37:49.820 --> 00:37:52.510
I wish I were that
open-minded and learned

00:37:52.510 --> 00:37:54.750
and had great experiences
like that more often.

00:37:57.550 --> 00:37:59.874
So that's a good case study.

00:37:59.874 --> 00:38:00.790
Anything to add, John?

00:38:00.790 --> 00:38:02.248
JOHN HEINS: I would
say a lot of it

00:38:02.248 --> 00:38:05.586
is understand why
you made a mistake.

00:38:05.586 --> 00:38:10.390
It may be that you didn't
really make a mistake.

00:38:10.390 --> 00:38:12.080
The analysis was
good, it was sound.

00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:14.790
And then something else
happened that made it go wrong.

00:38:14.790 --> 00:38:18.269
And so you shouldn't
necessarily--

00:38:18.269 --> 00:38:20.060
if you understand why
you made the mistake,

00:38:20.060 --> 00:38:22.610
you shouldn't
necessarily just not

00:38:22.610 --> 00:38:24.868
do that exact same
thing again next time.

00:38:24.868 --> 00:38:25.534
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:38:25.534 --> 00:38:26.710
I have two questions.

00:38:26.710 --> 00:38:30.224
The first one is your
portfolio has about 15 stocks.

00:38:30.224 --> 00:38:31.697
It has a very small
number, right?

00:38:31.697 --> 00:38:34.760
So how do you screen off
the thousands of stocks?

00:38:34.760 --> 00:38:37.120
What are some of the
top three or five

00:38:37.120 --> 00:38:39.261
factors you use as filters?

00:38:39.261 --> 00:38:40.010
That's number one.

00:38:40.010 --> 00:38:42.170
Number two is my
general impression

00:38:42.170 --> 00:38:46.200
is that the market tend to
ignore balance sheet items.

00:38:46.200 --> 00:38:50.390
So just like a lot of cash,
investment, the P/E number,

00:38:50.390 --> 00:38:52.520
totally ignore balance sheet.

00:38:52.520 --> 00:38:53.270
What do you think?

00:38:53.270 --> 00:38:55.934
How do you think
about that issue?

00:38:55.934 --> 00:38:58.100
WHITNEY TILSON: Well, I use
a four-step-- I actually

00:38:58.100 --> 00:38:59.849
have it taped to the
wall next to my desk.

00:38:59.849 --> 00:39:01.770
My four-step process
is first, when

00:39:01.770 --> 00:39:04.020
I look at any new stock
is circle of competence.

00:39:04.020 --> 00:39:05.930
Do I know something
about this industry?

00:39:05.930 --> 00:39:07.570
Is it knowable?

00:39:07.570 --> 00:39:10.100
Is the future predictable here?

00:39:12.940 --> 00:39:14.890
It's almost like
a yes or no thing.

00:39:14.890 --> 00:39:16.962
There is some gray
area where maybe I

00:39:16.962 --> 00:39:19.420
don't know it very well, but
I think I can do some research

00:39:19.420 --> 00:39:19.961
and get some.

00:39:19.961 --> 00:39:21.140
So circle of competence.

00:39:21.140 --> 00:39:25.864
Then it's do I like the company.

00:39:25.864 --> 00:39:27.530
And I look at financial
characteristics,

00:39:27.530 --> 00:39:29.420
cash flows, return
on equity, et cetera.

00:39:29.420 --> 00:39:30.569
So I evaluate the company.

00:39:30.569 --> 00:39:32.860
And by the way, I'll invest
in sort of crummy companies

00:39:32.860 --> 00:39:34.650
if it's cheap enough.

00:39:34.650 --> 00:39:37.320
But ideally I'm looking for
higher quality businesses

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:39.260
that I can compound over time.

00:39:39.260 --> 00:39:43.030
Then I look at the industry,
because a good company

00:39:43.030 --> 00:39:50.480
in a crummy industry,
eh, is going to struggle.

00:39:50.480 --> 00:39:55.394
So it's a company and industry
analysis, then management.

00:39:55.394 --> 00:39:56.560
And that's really important.

00:39:56.560 --> 00:39:58.660
Both, do they run
the business well?

00:39:58.660 --> 00:40:01.040
Do they allocate capital well?

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:04.500
And do they treat
shareholders well?

00:40:04.500 --> 00:40:06.010
And here's the thing.

00:40:06.010 --> 00:40:09.200
I can find-- right now I can
find hundreds of companies

00:40:09.200 --> 00:40:12.710
that I understand really well,
great industry and company

00:40:12.710 --> 00:40:17.140
dynamics, wonderful management,
treats shareholders great.

00:40:17.140 --> 00:40:18.710
So what's the problem?

00:40:18.710 --> 00:40:20.050
The stock's not cheap.

00:40:20.050 --> 00:40:23.084
Everybody else on
earth can understand it

00:40:23.084 --> 00:40:25.500
and likes the company and the
industry and the management,

00:40:25.500 --> 00:40:27.580
and therefore, the
stock price reflects it.

00:40:27.580 --> 00:40:30.780
The real key is to then just
sit there and sit there and sit

00:40:30.780 --> 00:40:34.970
there and sit there and be
super patient until I can find

00:40:34.970 --> 00:40:39.220
a situation where the stock
price is well below what

00:40:39.220 --> 00:40:43.260
I think it should be,
based on my analysis.

00:40:43.260 --> 00:40:45.575
And usually what
that requires is

00:40:45.575 --> 00:40:49.170
is for there to be
some-- the market thinks

00:40:49.170 --> 00:40:51.370
one thing, the variant
perception that John talked

00:40:51.370 --> 00:40:52.150
about.

00:40:52.150 --> 00:40:54.970
To make money investing you
only need to do two things.

00:40:54.970 --> 00:41:00.040
You need to bet against the
crowd-- that's the easy part.

00:41:00.040 --> 00:41:01.750
And then you just
have to be right.

00:41:01.750 --> 00:41:03.220
That's the hard part.

00:41:03.220 --> 00:41:05.190
Because the crowd
is usually right.

00:41:05.190 --> 00:41:06.640
The crowd was right on Google.

00:41:06.640 --> 00:41:09.300
If anything, the crowd didn't
appreciate Google enough.

00:41:09.300 --> 00:41:11.800
We now know, stock
was an 11-bagger.

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:12.880
So that's the hard part.

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:16.960
It just means being super,
super patient, and recognizing

00:41:16.960 --> 00:41:20.840
that nine out of 10 times
where you think your variant

00:41:20.840 --> 00:41:23.870
perception is right, nine out
of 10 times the crowd is right.

00:41:23.870 --> 00:41:26.800
The crowd is very wise
and powerful and smart,

00:41:26.800 --> 00:41:29.200
because there are a lot of
really smart people picking

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:29.860
over.

00:41:29.860 --> 00:41:31.767
And every time you
think, oh, this company's

00:41:31.767 --> 00:41:33.350
a really great company
and the stock's

00:41:33.350 --> 00:41:36.640
been unfairly beaten up, nine
out of 10 times you're wrong.

00:41:36.640 --> 00:41:39.970
The company's in full scale
collapse and it's a value trap.

00:41:39.970 --> 00:41:42.880
So what I try and do
is once a month, once

00:41:42.880 --> 00:41:45.050
every two months
or three months,

00:41:45.050 --> 00:41:47.600
I look at a lot of
different things.

00:41:47.600 --> 00:41:51.295
It's like a pitcher
pitching to you in baseball.

00:41:51.295 --> 00:41:53.420
You sit there and they
don't call balls or strikes.

00:41:53.420 --> 00:41:55.586
You can just sit there and
take pitches all day long

00:41:55.586 --> 00:41:58.110
and don't swing at anything
that's a little iffy.

00:41:58.110 --> 00:42:01.505
Wait till just something
that you just in your gut

00:42:01.505 --> 00:42:06.520
you know that I know I'm right
on this one and the market's

00:42:06.520 --> 00:42:07.440
wrong on this one.

00:42:07.440 --> 00:42:10.730
And that's when you swing.

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:13.350
JOHN HEINS: His second question
was about balance sheets?

00:42:13.350 --> 00:42:16.370
Is that your perception
that-- I don't

00:42:16.370 --> 00:42:20.460
know if that's universally held,
the idea that balance sheet

00:42:20.460 --> 00:42:21.710
assets are ignored.

00:42:21.710 --> 00:42:26.240
Actually, it's one of the--
it is a way value investors

00:42:26.240 --> 00:42:29.960
I think find value is that
there isn't a recognition.

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:33.280
There isn't a recognition
that, well, the stock's really

00:42:33.280 --> 00:42:34.960
pretty cheap when you
take out the cash,

00:42:34.960 --> 00:42:37.430
or maybe that there are assets
on the books that are just

00:42:37.430 --> 00:42:40.150
wildly more valuable than
they currently trade.

00:42:40.150 --> 00:42:43.730
So that is a typical
way in which investors

00:42:43.730 --> 00:42:47.610
do assess something to
be inefficiently priced.

00:42:47.610 --> 00:42:51.460
So I wouldn't say it always
happens, but it certainly it

00:42:51.460 --> 00:42:53.870
is a way to find value.

00:42:53.870 --> 00:42:55.780
WHITNEY TILSON: I
mean historically,

00:42:55.780 --> 00:42:58.050
Ben Graham was a balance
sheet investor-- just

00:42:58.050 --> 00:42:59.190
buy things net nets.

00:42:59.190 --> 00:43:03.070
Things trading at discount
to readily ascertainable

00:43:03.070 --> 00:43:05.910
liquidation value, excluding
property, plant and equipment.

00:43:05.910 --> 00:43:09.050
Just like accounts receivable,
cash, minus all liabilities,

00:43:09.050 --> 00:43:10.330
et cetera.

00:43:10.330 --> 00:43:12.717
And Buffett moved away from
that for a very good reason.

00:43:12.717 --> 00:43:14.550
They tend to be super
low quality companies.

00:43:14.550 --> 00:43:16.170
A lot of value traps.

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:18.670
Difficult to do if you're
managing any kind of material

00:43:18.670 --> 00:43:21.390
pool of capital, because there
tend to be nooks and crannies.

00:43:21.390 --> 00:43:25.120
Every once in a while,
late 2008, early 2009,

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:29.274
they are statistically cheap on
a balance sheet basis companies

00:43:29.274 --> 00:43:31.690
where you could have gone and
just bought a basket of them

00:43:31.690 --> 00:43:33.000
and made quite a bit of money.

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:34.560
But it's hard to do.

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:38.470
Only once every 10 years
does that sort of work.

00:43:38.470 --> 00:43:41.280
So usually during times of
market panic, and at that point

00:43:41.280 --> 00:43:44.980
you're probably better off
buying higher quality companies

00:43:44.980 --> 00:43:47.340
that you just don't
buy for a quick double,

00:43:47.340 --> 00:43:49.815
but if all the stocks
are really depressed,

00:43:49.815 --> 00:43:51.649
you can get a long run on them.

00:43:51.649 --> 00:43:52.940
Is there a question back there?

00:43:52.940 --> 00:43:53.340
Or here.

