00:44:52.624 --> 00:44:53.290
Whatever, right?

00:44:53.290 --> 00:44:56.060
Like I've got a lot of training,
plus a lot of experience.

00:44:56.060 --> 00:45:00.540
This is an experience-based
business, and very, very--

00:45:00.540 --> 00:45:07.560
and it's a business that 80+% of
people engaged in the business

00:45:07.560 --> 00:45:10.220
full-time really don't
know what they're doing,

00:45:10.220 --> 00:45:14.160
and are going to do
worse than an index fund.

00:45:14.160 --> 00:45:18.820
So I'd like to think
I'm in the 20% that

00:45:18.820 --> 00:45:20.930
has enough experience
and enough training,

00:45:20.930 --> 00:45:23.940
is sort of smart and
clever enough to do better

00:45:23.940 --> 00:45:26.870
for my investors
than index funds.

00:45:26.870 --> 00:45:29.964
But as a general rule,
it's hard to pick stocks.

00:45:29.964 --> 00:45:31.380
It's hard to pick
managers who are

00:45:31.380 --> 00:45:33.130
skilled at picking
stocks over time.

00:45:33.130 --> 00:45:36.120
Because I can tell you we've
had a six year bull market.

00:45:36.120 --> 00:45:39.220
There are a lot of bull market
geniuses out there right now

00:45:39.220 --> 00:45:42.642
who have just been piling in
to the most speculative stocks,

00:45:42.642 --> 00:45:44.100
and they've been
rewarded for that.

00:45:44.100 --> 00:45:45.870
And so they have the
best track records

00:45:45.870 --> 00:45:47.502
over the last six years.

00:45:47.502 --> 00:45:49.460
And a lot of them weren't
running money in '08.

00:45:49.460 --> 00:45:51.810
So the most important
thing I tell you in looking

00:45:51.810 --> 00:45:55.127
at a manager is look at how they
did in '08, and that can tell

00:45:55.127 --> 00:45:57.460
you what kind of risk takers
they are and how they might

00:45:57.460 --> 00:45:58.530
form in a down market.

00:45:58.530 --> 00:46:00.363
But the problem is the
average money manager

00:46:00.363 --> 00:46:02.690
hasn't been in
business six years.

00:46:02.690 --> 00:46:04.930
And so therefore, you can't
see how they did in '08.

00:46:04.930 --> 00:46:09.920
So that's why I'm a
big fan of index funds.

00:46:09.920 --> 00:46:11.830
Those books are
right, by and large.

00:46:11.830 --> 00:46:15.910
But there are also outliers
that is not random.

00:46:15.910 --> 00:46:18.450
Warren Buffett's track
record is not random.

00:46:18.450 --> 00:46:19.920
He's just that
good, and there are

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:22.172
some guys who are that good.

00:46:22.172 --> 00:46:23.630
AUDIENCE: I just
finished your book

00:46:23.630 --> 00:46:26.722
and it was very, very excellent.

00:46:26.722 --> 00:46:28.430
One of the things I
noticed is that a lot

00:46:28.430 --> 00:46:31.280
of these excellent
stock experts are

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:34.376
very forthcoming with their
ideas and their philosophy,

00:46:34.376 --> 00:46:36.360
and very much in detail.

00:46:36.360 --> 00:46:40.100
And yet, it seems like the
vast majority of people

00:46:40.100 --> 00:46:41.550
