00:47:29.780 --> 00:47:33.750
through the discipline of
their buy and sell mechanisms,

00:47:33.750 --> 00:47:37.280
they're able to stick with
that through thick or thin.

00:47:37.280 --> 00:47:40.280
And that is really hard.

00:47:40.280 --> 00:47:42.740
Joel Greenblatt-- he's quoted
several times in the book,

00:47:42.740 --> 00:47:46.160
and he talks about it's
really hard, because you

00:47:46.160 --> 00:47:49.150
can be wrong for-- a
lot of value investors

00:47:49.150 --> 00:47:50.180
are struggling now.

00:47:50.180 --> 00:47:54.050
Market's gone up for
five straight years,

00:47:54.050 --> 00:47:56.910
so they're struggling, they feel
out of sync with the market.

00:47:56.910 --> 00:48:03.280
And you want to just fix that,
but you have to resist that.

00:48:03.280 --> 00:48:05.250
Because fixing it means
going against what

00:48:05.250 --> 00:48:07.145
your discipline is, and
what your process is,

00:48:07.145 --> 00:48:08.500
and what you believe in.

00:48:08.500 --> 00:48:14.590
And so I think an ability
through the hard times

00:48:14.590 --> 00:48:16.360
to stick with what
you believe in

00:48:16.360 --> 00:48:19.640
and execute it without
cutting corners

00:48:19.640 --> 00:48:20.920
in a real disciplined way.

00:48:20.920 --> 00:48:23.480
It's really kind of basic
blocking and tackling.

00:48:23.480 --> 00:48:25.860
But I think that's what sets
a lot of these people apart.

00:48:25.860 --> 00:48:27.670
Obviously, they're very smart.

00:48:27.670 --> 00:48:31.720
Warren Buffett always
talks about it's not

00:48:31.720 --> 00:48:33.970
the person with the highest
IQ that wins in investing.

00:48:33.970 --> 00:48:37.170
But clearly, Warren
Buffett is pretty smart.

00:48:37.170 --> 00:48:39.676
So yeah, it doesn't hurt.

00:48:39.676 --> 00:48:41.800
WHITNEY TILSON: So this
article I wrote three years

00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:43.790
before the infamous
Google article.

00:48:43.790 --> 00:48:46.060
July, 2001, "Traits of
Successful Money Managers."

00:48:46.060 --> 00:48:47.270
I framed it in two things.

00:48:47.270 --> 00:48:49.030
To be a successful stock
picker or money manager,

00:48:49.030 --> 00:48:49.890
you had to do two things.

00:48:49.890 --> 00:48:50.920
You have to have
the right approach,

00:48:50.920 --> 00:48:53.270
and then you have to be
able-- the right temperament.

00:48:53.270 --> 00:48:54.230
You have to be able to execute.

00:48:54.230 --> 00:48:56.563
So you have to have the right
sort of philosophy, right?

00:48:56.563 --> 00:48:58.710
So you're not trading
electrons or whatever.

00:48:58.710 --> 00:49:02.130
You're buying companies, you
only buy when it's on sale,

00:49:02.130 --> 00:49:07.357
you sort of ignore the market,
focus on avoiding losses,

00:49:07.357 --> 00:49:09.190
only invest when the
odds are in your favor,

00:49:09.190 --> 00:49:12.486
don't worry about macroeconomic
factors, et cetera, et cetera.

00:49:12.486 --> 00:49:14.110
So you have to have
the right approach.

00:49:14.110 --> 00:49:15.818
And then you have to
be the right person.

00:49:15.818 --> 00:49:17.142
And so what does that mean?

00:49:17.142 --> 00:49:18.600
You're a business
person and you're

00:49:18.600 --> 00:49:20.750
thinking about you're
buying businesses.

00:49:20.750 --> 00:49:22.410
You have the private
equity mentality.

00:49:22.410 --> 00:49:25.070
If I could buy this entire
business for the market

00:49:25.070 --> 00:49:27.810
cap, which I am buying one
share of this business,

00:49:27.810 --> 00:49:29.190
that's what I would do.

00:49:29.190 --> 00:49:30.400
You have to be really smart.

00:49:30.400 --> 00:49:32.000
You have to have a lot of
intellectual horsepower,

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:32.550
for sure.

00:49:32.550 --> 00:49:34.640
But then once you
reach a certain level,

00:49:34.640 --> 00:49:37.290
the ability to crunch
numbers, mathematical ability,

00:49:37.290 --> 00:49:43.480
is a pretty low importance
above a fairly basic level.

00:49:43.480 --> 00:49:45.354
And then it comes
to the mental stuff

00:49:45.354 --> 00:49:46.520
that you were talking about.

00:49:46.520 --> 00:49:49.790
So you have to be simultaneously
confident and humble.

00:49:49.790 --> 00:49:52.820
Nobody gets into this business
without a lot of confidence.

00:49:52.820 --> 00:49:54.770
It's just that's the
nature of the business.

00:49:54.770 --> 00:49:56.520
Your track record is public.

00:49:56.520 --> 00:49:59.890
Any time you're betting against
1,000, a million other people,

00:49:59.890 --> 00:50:01.170
that is an act of arrogance.

00:50:01.170 --> 00:50:03.540
The purchase of a stock
is an act of arrogance

00:50:03.540 --> 00:50:05.694
because you're saying
I think I'm right,

00:50:05.694 --> 00:50:07.360
and all those million
other smart people

00:50:07.360 --> 00:50:10.160
and plus their
supercomputers are wrong.

00:50:10.160 --> 00:50:12.010
It's an act of arrogance.

00:50:12.010 --> 00:50:14.010
So you have to have
that kind of confidence.

00:50:14.010 --> 00:50:16.799
But at the same time, you
have to have the humility

00:50:16.799 --> 00:50:18.840
to recognize when something's
outside your circle

00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:19.650
of competence.

00:50:19.650 --> 00:50:24.060
To recognize if your
investment thesis is wrong,

00:50:24.060 --> 00:50:26.400
and to accept
disconfirming information

00:50:26.400 --> 00:50:27.680
and change your mind.

00:50:27.680 --> 00:50:31.300
And sometimes very publicly
admit that you were wrong.

00:50:31.300 --> 00:50:33.590
And then you have to just
be really independent.

00:50:33.590 --> 00:50:36.580
It doesn't matter if everybody
else loves the stock.

00:50:36.580 --> 00:50:39.670
If everybody else hates the
stock, you have to not care.

00:50:39.670 --> 00:50:43.050
You have to do your own
analysis, value the company,

00:50:43.050 --> 00:50:44.770
and then buy it--
be patient enough

00:50:44.770 --> 00:50:47.190
to buy it at sort
of half that price.

00:50:47.190 --> 00:50:50.570
And lastly, sort of be
patient-- long-term greedy.

00:50:50.570 --> 00:50:53.900
Most human beings are hardwired
try and get rich quick.

00:50:53.900 --> 00:50:56.460
Who doesn't want to
get rich quick, right?

00:50:56.460 --> 00:50:58.360
You've got to have
the patience to be

00:50:58.360 --> 00:51:02.160
willing to get rich slowly.

00:51:02.160 --> 00:51:05.230
And you will make money faster
with the get rich slowly

00:51:05.230 --> 00:51:08.040
approach than with the
get rich quick approach.

00:51:08.040 --> 00:51:09.520
And lastly I'll
just say the people

00:51:09.520 --> 00:51:11.686
who are really good at this,
they love what they do.

00:51:11.686 --> 00:51:14.040
Like I was talking with
Richie earlier and said,

00:51:14.040 --> 00:51:16.640
people here at Google, like
a lot of people I work with

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:21.160
and so forth, they love
tackling challenging

00:51:21.160 --> 00:51:22.220
intellectual problems.

00:51:22.220 --> 00:51:24.300
They love what they do.

00:51:24.300 --> 00:51:27.200
They're not here for
the money, primarily.

00:51:27.200 --> 00:51:28.510
They love what they do.

00:51:28.510 --> 00:51:32.280
I can tell you in my business,
the successful investors

00:51:32.280 --> 00:51:33.060
love what they do.

00:51:33.060 --> 00:51:35.780
It happens to be
extremely lucrative,

00:51:35.780 --> 00:51:38.300
and nobody minds the
money, I suppose.

00:51:38.300 --> 00:51:43.160
But if you took away the money,
every single investor I know,

00:51:43.160 --> 00:51:45.350
the good investors, would
still keep investing,

00:51:45.350 --> 00:51:47.100
because they love the
game, the challenge,

00:51:47.100 --> 00:51:51.390
the intellectual
challenge, the feedback you

00:51:51.390 --> 00:51:54.790
get in fairly short order,
like if your analysis is

00:51:54.790 --> 00:51:56.410
right or not.

00:51:56.410 --> 00:51:58.450
I think there was a
question back there.

00:51:58.450 --> 00:52:01.380
I don't want to
miss your question.

