But we wore secondhand clothes.

00:59:20.170 --> 00:59:23.000
My parents never owned a
new car their entire life.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:24.880
And we didn't go
out to eat a lot.

00:59:24.880 --> 00:59:26.580
And my mom's a good
cook and whatever.

00:59:26.580 --> 00:59:28.610
And so every year
they just salted away

00:59:28.610 --> 00:59:30.900
money, and you save
money-- and this

00:59:30.900 --> 00:59:33.660
is a very high cost
of living area.

00:59:33.660 --> 00:59:36.770
But there are ways to
not be extravagant.

00:59:36.770 --> 00:59:38.504
And so the single
most important thing

00:59:38.504 --> 00:59:40.420
you can do for your
long-term financial health

00:59:40.420 --> 00:59:42.110
is just live beneath your means.

00:59:42.110 --> 00:59:44.230
Certainly don't be out on
margin with your credit

00:59:44.230 --> 00:59:45.960
cards paying 25% interest.

00:59:45.960 --> 00:59:47.250
So that's number one.

00:59:47.250 --> 00:59:52.550
Number two is is unless you
really know a manager of fund

00:59:52.550 --> 00:59:57.630
well or whatever, indexing
is actually a great option.

00:59:57.630 --> 01:00:00.360
If you ask me to pick a mutual
fund to recommend to you,

01:00:00.360 --> 01:00:01.480
I know one mutual fund.

01:00:01.480 --> 01:00:02.980
Of the 8,000 mutual
funds out there,

01:00:02.980 --> 01:00:04.580
there's only one
I would recommend,

01:00:04.580 --> 01:00:05.950
and it's a guy I happen to know.

01:00:05.950 --> 01:00:09.167
Zeke Ashton runs the Centaur
total return fund or whatever.

01:00:09.167 --> 01:00:11.500
It's a relatively small fund,
but I know him personally,

01:00:11.500 --> 01:00:12.958
and I would have
confidence in him.

01:00:12.958 --> 01:00:13.680
And that's it.

01:00:13.680 --> 01:00:14.340
That's it.

01:00:14.340 --> 01:00:15.350
So just index.

01:00:15.350 --> 01:00:18.280
And I've been doing
this 16 years.

01:00:18.280 --> 01:00:19.940
And then thirdly,
you guys are sort of

01:00:19.940 --> 01:00:21.840
in an interesting position here.

01:00:21.840 --> 01:00:22.780
You guys have friends.

01:00:22.780 --> 01:00:27.050
You're in the heart of
an incredibly vibrant,

01:00:27.050 --> 01:00:30.690
dynamic area with
incredible companies.

01:00:30.690 --> 01:00:36.260
And I don't think buying Tesla
or Netflix today is probably

01:00:36.260 --> 01:00:39.450
going to be the wisest
thing, or Apple today,

01:00:39.450 --> 01:00:42.190
after they've run
up 20x or more.

01:00:42.190 --> 01:00:44.700
But it's a volatile sector.

01:00:44.700 --> 01:00:49.330
And to the extent a particular
company's stock gets killed

01:00:49.330 --> 01:00:51.520
or the whole sector
gets killed, you guys

01:00:51.520 --> 01:00:53.410
are actually in a
reasonable position

01:00:53.410 --> 01:00:54.980
if you talk to your
friends and you

01:00:54.980 --> 01:00:57.130
look at where's
the talent flowing.

01:00:57.130 --> 01:01:00.700
It is flowing out of
Yahoo and into Facebook.

01:01:00.700 --> 01:01:02.720
And Facebook got
killed post IPO and it

01:01:02.720 --> 01:01:07.504
went from 50 or something,
down to 20 or something.

01:01:07.504 --> 01:01:09.920
You guys actually might have
been able to figure that out,

01:01:09.920 --> 01:01:11.320
whereas I wasn't.

01:01:11.320 --> 01:01:12.610
Because I'm not out here.

01:01:12.610 --> 01:01:13.990
I don't know the people at all.

01:01:13.990 --> 01:01:17.220
But Facebook, I think you guys
have the second best business

01:01:17.220 --> 01:01:18.090
model in the world.

01:01:18.090 --> 01:01:20.631
I actually think Facebook may
well have the greatest business

01:01:20.631 --> 01:01:22.230
model in the world.

01:01:22.230 --> 01:01:24.350
It's a winner-take-all business.

01:01:24.350 --> 01:01:29.100
It's one out of every six people
on the planet is now a member.

01:01:29.100 --> 01:01:31.610
And it costs them nothing
to add new members.

01:01:31.610 --> 01:01:35.510
There's zero incremental cost,
so they just grow globally

01:01:35.510 --> 01:01:39.150
at no incremental cost,
and it's just pure profit.

01:01:39.150 --> 01:01:41.280
It's pretty incredible.

01:01:41.280 --> 01:01:43.040
That business model
never existed before.

01:01:43.040 --> 01:01:44.840
You guys have very
similar dynamics.

01:01:44.840 --> 01:01:47.150
So it would be close, right?

01:01:47.150 --> 01:01:49.000
Well, compare that
to a Tesla, which

01:01:49.000 --> 01:01:51.990
is I was stupid enough to short,
and then gained appreciation

01:01:51.990 --> 01:01:54.530
for it and think it's
an incredible company.

01:01:54.530 --> 01:01:56.625
But you see, they actually
have to make stuff,

01:01:56.625 --> 01:01:58.250
and then they have
to ship it, and they

01:01:58.250 --> 01:01:59.791
have inventory, et
cetera, et cetera.

01:01:59.791 --> 01:02:03.570
For them to grow it's a very
capital-intensive process.

01:02:03.570 --> 01:02:07.200
They have nowhere near the
business model you guys have

01:02:07.200 --> 01:02:08.420
or Facebook has.

01:02:08.420 --> 01:02:12.480
So you guys, I would say maybe
take 20% of your portfolio

01:02:12.480 --> 01:02:15.600
and use your networks
and relationships

01:02:15.600 --> 01:02:18.800
and where the smartest people
you know all go into work.

01:02:18.800 --> 01:02:20.380
And when that
company comes public,

01:02:20.380 --> 01:02:22.960
if it craps out post
IPO or something,

01:02:22.960 --> 01:02:24.230
don't buy at the peak.

01:02:24.230 --> 01:02:26.110
Wait until there's a crap out.

01:02:26.110 --> 01:02:28.830
And you guys should be able
to, with a very little amount

01:02:28.830 --> 01:02:31.795
of your time, just based on
your own knowledge, expertise

01:02:31.795 --> 01:02:34.920
and relationships, be able to
find a few of these beaten down

01:02:34.920 --> 01:02:37.860
companies with a small
enough amount of money

01:02:37.860 --> 01:02:40.089
that you're not going to
stress about it too much.

01:02:40.089 --> 01:02:41.630
AUDIENCE: You
mentioned earlier, when

01:02:41.630 --> 01:02:43.360
determining the
value of a company

01:02:43.360 --> 01:02:46.090
that one factor is
market sentiment, how

01:02:46.090 --> 01:02:48.010
people feel about the company.

01:02:48.010 --> 01:02:51.050
And you also mentioned the
word supercomputer earlier.

01:02:51.050 --> 01:02:52.620
So I have a question about that.

01:02:52.620 --> 01:02:55.970
One, market sentiment seems to
be, for lack of a better term,

01:02:55.970 --> 01:02:56.850
crazy these days.

01:02:56.850 --> 01:03:00.630
I mean people look at a company,
it'll go up 10% on Tuesday

01:03:00.630 --> 01:03:03.900
and down 20% on Wednesday.

01:03:03.900 --> 01:03:05.640
And maybe
supercomputers, the way

01:03:05.640 --> 01:03:07.930
they interfere in
the market now,

01:03:07.930 --> 01:03:10.250
may be amplifying
this by reacting

01:03:10.250 --> 01:03:12.790
to momentum, et cetera.

01:03:12.790 --> 01:03:15.580
So with the value
of a company being

01:03:15.580 --> 01:03:19.050
so skewed sometimes
over a very long time,

01:03:19.050 --> 01:03:22.380
is value investing harder or
less effective these days?

01:03:22.380 --> 01:03:24.995
And is that trend going to
continue in your opinion?

01:03:28.570 --> 01:03:30.890
WHITNEY TILSON: It's
definitely harder now,

01:03:30.890 --> 01:03:34.160
but I'm not sure that reflects
a long-term fundamental shift.

01:03:34.160 --> 01:03:36.560
It just tends to be hard
when markets are complacent,

01:03:36.560 --> 01:03:40.120
and stocks, the markets
are at all-time highs.

01:03:40.120 --> 01:03:42.690
But I wouldn't call the
market out there crazy.

01:03:42.690 --> 01:03:47.050
I mean the multiple of the S&amp;P
500 today's 16 or 17 times.

01:03:47.050 --> 01:03:51.160
It was well north of 30
times in 1999, for example.

01:03:51.160 --> 01:03:54.600
That was pure insanity.

01:03:54.600 --> 01:03:58.170
There are pockets of
foolishness out there, for sure.

01:03:58.170 --> 01:04:01.220
But sort of getting
back to your question

01:04:01.220 --> 01:04:04.310
back there about how do you
invest in today's world.

01:04:04.310 --> 01:04:06.600
There's nothing real
easy right there.

01:04:06.600 --> 01:04:10.035
I mean stocks, if you
ask me the S&amp;P 500,

01:04:10.035 --> 01:04:11.410
if you just bought
an index fund,

01:04:11.410 --> 01:04:13.970
you can make 5%, 6% a year
over the next 10 years.

01:04:13.970 --> 01:04:15.270
Yeah, that's not horrible.

01:04:15.270 --> 01:04:16.600
It's not very exciting.

01:04:16.600 --> 01:04:24.550
But when bonds are
offering you virtually nil,

01:04:24.550 --> 01:04:27.710
you just can't get discouraged,
and you can't get impatient,

01:04:27.710 --> 01:04:29.280
and you can't swing
for the fences.

01:04:29.280 --> 01:04:31.150
Can't say, you know, I'm not
happy with an index fund.

01:04:31.150 --> 01:04:32.270
I'm not happy with bonds.

01:04:32.270 --> 01:04:34.646
So I'm going to go
buy Astroturf.com

01:04:34.646 --> 01:04:38.120
when it comes public, or
do something stupid, right?

01:04:38.120 --> 01:04:40.610
So you just have to be patient.

01:04:40.610 --> 01:04:42.150
And be content.

01:04:42.150 --> 01:04:44.110
We're in sort of a
low return world,

01:04:44.110 --> 01:04:46.700
so hang out, live
beneath your means,

01:04:46.700 --> 01:04:50.060
save money, and wait for
better opportunities.

01:04:50.060 --> 01:04:52.310
JOHN HEINS: To your question
about the supercomputers,

01:04:52.310 --> 01:04:55.080
I think what a classic
traditional value

01:04:55.080 --> 01:04:59.870
investor would say is that the
fewer decisions about a stock

01:04:59.870 --> 01:05:06.400
price that are being made
by humans, the opportunity

01:05:06.400 --> 01:05:09.630
is actually better, because
there will be more volatility.

01:05:09.630 --> 01:05:11.962
Volatility is a good thing.

01:05:11.962 --> 01:05:14.170
Value investors tend to find
volatility a good thing.

01:05:14.170 --> 01:05:18.690
So if, for whatever
algorithm-driven reasons,

01:05:18.690 --> 01:05:22.630
a stock does go down 20%--
it could go up 20% too,

01:05:22.630 --> 01:05:27.330
but if it does go down 20% on
a day because of some news,

01:05:27.330 --> 01:05:30.490
and then the momentum of the
stock then forced it down

01:05:30.490 --> 01:05:32.540
farther than it
would go otherwise.

01:05:32.540 --> 01:05:35.930
If you're alert, if
you're paying attention,

01:05:35.930 --> 01:05:38.739
if you have a clear sense
of what something is worth,

01:05:38.739 --> 01:05:40.030
you can take advantage of that.

01:05:40.030 --> 01:05:43.330
So that's what a classic
traditional value

01:05:43.330 --> 01:05:45.060
investor will say.

01:05:45.060 --> 01:05:47.130
They won't say it's
easy, but the volatility

01:05:47.130 --> 01:05:49.810
is not something that
worries them or bothers them.

01:05:49.810 --> 01:05:51.970
AUDIENCE: Value
investing historically

01:05:51.970 --> 01:05:56.370
has been compared to performance
of indexes such as the S&amp;P

01:05:56.370 --> 01:05:57.620
index.

01:05:57.620 --> 01:06:00.620
And it seems to me, as long as
they beat the market, the S&amp;P

01:06:00.620 --> 01:06:03.420
index, for example, then
value investors are happy.

01:06:03.420 --> 01:06:05.946
But I want to question
this a little bit.

01:06:05.946 --> 01:06:08.070
So value investing has been
around for a long time.

01:06:08.070 --> 01:06:12.710
And credit should be given to
people who actually discovered

01:06:12.710 --> 01:06:16.440
it and pioneered this--
Ben Graham, Warren Buffett.

01:06:16.440 --> 01:06:18.750
But they're not
passive solutions.

01:06:18.750 --> 01:06:21.900
For example, they mention
those-- value investing

01:06:21.900 --> 01:06:23.530
fund was mentioned.

01:06:23.530 --> 01:06:27.140
So isn't that actually a better
benchmark to compare against?

01:06:27.140 --> 01:06:32.030
And a study by [INAUDIBLE],
if I remember correctly,

01:06:32.030 --> 01:06:32.692
comes to mind.

01:06:32.692 --> 01:06:34.150
And this comparison
actually didn't

01:06:34.150 --> 01:06:39.800
look very good to funds
that were cited earlier

01:06:39.800 --> 01:06:40.880
in the survey.

01:06:40.880 --> 01:06:42.590
Tweedy, Browne, for example.

01:06:42.590 --> 01:06:45.720
So do you compare
against such benchmarks?

01:06:45.720 --> 01:06:53.594
And do you think value
investing is still beneficial?

01:06:53.594 --> 01:06:55.260
WHITNEY TILSON: I
guess my first thought

01:06:55.260 --> 01:06:57.640
is is I think the
studies are correct.

01:06:57.640 --> 01:07:01.130
Mutual funds
collectively, as a whole,

01:07:01.130 --> 01:07:04.190
underperform the market by
roughly their amount of fees,

01:07:04.190 --> 01:07:06.390
plus some trading
costs, et cetera.

01:07:06.390 --> 01:07:08.736
And hedge funds
underperform even more,

01:07:08.736 --> 01:07:11.360
because they're just higher fees
and have higher trading costs.

01:07:11.360 --> 01:07:14.340
So collectively speaking, the
studies are exactly right.

01:07:14.340 --> 01:07:17.880
As for which benchmark I
choose to use or whatever is

01:07:17.880 --> 01:07:21.830
it depends on what you're
trying to accomplish

01:07:21.830 --> 01:07:24.250
and what your
investors' goals are.

01:07:24.250 --> 01:07:27.500
My investors are all
individual investors.

01:07:27.500 --> 01:07:33.676
My parents own nothing except--
no other funds other than mine.

01:07:33.676 --> 01:07:35.550
And then I've just parked
them in index funds

01:07:35.550 --> 01:07:37.200
for the rest of it,
and then some in cash

01:07:37.200 --> 01:07:38.574
and bonds-- a
little bit of that,

01:07:38.574 --> 01:07:43.070
because they're in their 70s
and they want a little cushion.

01:07:43.070 --> 01:07:45.690
So most of my investors
are individual investors

01:07:45.690 --> 01:07:48.390
and their default
option is the S&amp;P 500.

01:07:48.390 --> 01:07:50.560
So that's what I should
compare myself to, right?

01:07:50.560 --> 01:07:53.540
But there are plenty of
institutional investors

01:07:53.540 --> 01:07:55.190
that are looking at
a hedge fund that

01:07:55.190 --> 01:07:58.050
is running a
market-neutral-- they have

01:07:58.050 --> 01:08:00.329
the same long exposure
as short exposure,

01:08:00.329 --> 01:08:02.120
and they're just trying
to be a little more

01:08:02.120 --> 01:08:04.036
clever on their longs
and a little more clever

01:08:04.036 --> 01:08:07.380
on the shorts to grind
out 8% to 10% returns.

01:08:07.380 --> 01:08:09.950
And last year when the market
was up 34 and the hedge fund

01:08:09.950 --> 01:08:12.220
was up 10%, those
investors were happy

01:08:12.220 --> 01:08:17.260
because their alternative was
a bond or something in cash,

01:08:17.260 --> 01:08:19.999
and they got 10%.

01:08:19.999 --> 01:08:21.540
But that's the kind
of fund they were

01:08:21.540 --> 01:08:24.080
investing in that was delivering
that kind of performance.

01:08:24.080 --> 01:08:26.560
So there's no right
or wrong answer here.

01:08:26.560 --> 01:08:30.830
It's just a question of
what the fund manager thinks

01:08:30.830 --> 01:08:33.029
that they're good at and
what their strategy is,

01:08:33.029 --> 01:08:37.470
and therefore,
they would say this

01:08:37.470 --> 01:08:39.550
is the benchmark we
compare ourselves to.

01:08:39.550 --> 01:08:42.652
And then investors can come
in and decide whether that's

01:08:42.652 --> 01:08:45.110
what they're looking for, and
then you evaluate the manager

01:08:45.110 --> 01:08:48.170
and see whether-- OK, do I think
the manager can execute on this

01:08:48.170 --> 01:08:50.630
and outperform the benchmark.

01:08:54.069 --> 01:08:57.090
JOHN HEINS: I still believe
that value investing works.

01:08:57.090 --> 01:09:00.410
And that value investing,
it does perform over time.

01:09:00.410 --> 01:09:02.580
It has to be executed well.

01:09:02.580 --> 01:09:06.750
But I believe it
works, and I think

01:09:06.750 --> 01:09:09.740
research would show that
executed well, it does work.

01:09:09.740 --> 01:09:11.359
Now, one can
question whether you

01:09:11.359 --> 01:09:13.109
can find the right
people to do it,

01:09:13.109 --> 01:09:15.410
but to the point, the
dimensional funds, those types

01:09:15.410 --> 01:09:18.200
of things, it is a value
investing philosophy

01:09:18.200 --> 01:09:20.580
that is different than an index.

01:09:20.580 --> 01:09:22.729
And if you believe
in value investing,

01:09:22.729 --> 01:09:26.750
you could argue that it's
better than an index.

01:09:26.750 --> 01:09:29.850
AUDIENCE: So this question
is about you mentioning

01:09:29.850 --> 01:09:32.609
that you go an extra
step, and also look

01:09:32.609 --> 01:09:35.044
for the reason of
the mispricing as

01:09:35.044 --> 01:09:36.710
to why things have
been-- John mentioned

01:09:36.710 --> 01:09:39.970
that in one of his slides.

01:09:39.970 --> 01:09:42.590
So what is the
rationale behind it?

01:09:42.590 --> 01:09:44.160
Let's say there is
a stock which you

01:09:44.160 --> 01:09:46.700
think is mispriced
because of neglect.

01:09:46.700 --> 01:09:48.160
How does that help?

01:09:48.160 --> 01:09:50.481
How stringent is
this philosophy?

01:09:50.481 --> 01:09:52.189
Like if you're not
able to find a reason,

01:09:52.189 --> 01:09:53.147
do you just not invest?

01:09:56.150 --> 01:09:58.800
JOHN HEINS: I think not
everyone would say that.

01:09:58.800 --> 01:10:02.591
I chose one of the quotes where
he was talking about he really

01:10:02.591 --> 01:10:03.965
believed that that
was important.

01:10:06.610 --> 01:10:10.800
I think the thought
process is that there

01:10:10.800 --> 01:10:15.000
are a lot of things
you can miss.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:17.690
There may be reasons
why you missed something

01:10:17.690 --> 01:10:20.930
and it was going to
make the stock go up

01:10:20.930 --> 01:10:24.500
and you didn't buy it, or it was
going to make the stock go down

01:10:24.500 --> 01:10:25.920
and you didn't think of it.

01:10:25.920 --> 01:10:28.470
So I think it's
more of a discipline

01:10:28.470 --> 01:10:34.010
to identify, not just content
yourself with oh, it's cheap

01:10:34.010 --> 01:10:35.820
and I don't know why.

01:10:35.820 --> 01:10:37.980
Because you may miss that.

01:10:37.980 --> 01:10:40.930
You may dismiss it.

01:10:40.930 --> 01:10:43.420
I missed something
important, and so try

01:10:43.420 --> 01:10:45.900
to find out why it's mispriced.

01:10:45.900 --> 01:10:48.060
And not everyone
tells me that, but I

01:10:48.060 --> 01:10:51.730
chose that one because
I hear that often

01:10:51.730 --> 01:10:53.304
and it makes sense to me.

01:10:53.304 --> 01:10:54.720
WHITNEY TILSON:
Look, any time you

01:10:54.720 --> 01:10:57.450
buy stock you're
betting against-- you

01:10:57.450 --> 01:11:00.700
think it's cheap
because the market is

01:11:00.700 --> 01:11:02.140
failing to appreciate.

01:11:02.140 --> 01:11:03.547
The market thinks
something worse

01:11:03.547 --> 01:11:05.130
about the company
than what you think.

01:11:05.130 --> 01:11:07.296
That's why the stock is
trading less than intrinsic,

01:11:07.296 --> 01:11:09.210
and what you believe
intrinsic value is.

01:11:09.210 --> 01:11:11.570
Being very clear
and understanding

01:11:11.570 --> 01:11:14.297
what the market
believes is important

01:11:14.297 --> 01:11:16.130
so that you can figure
out what's different.

01:11:16.130 --> 01:11:17.504
That would be the
problem I would

01:11:17.504 --> 01:11:20.340
have about investing
in Google stock today.

01:11:20.340 --> 01:11:24.900
Because what do I believe that
is so much better about Google

01:11:24.900 --> 01:11:26.460
than the consensus view.

01:11:26.460 --> 01:11:28.750
Because the consensus view
is you guys are awesome,

01:11:28.750 --> 01:11:30.435
and it's an incredible
company, and it

01:11:30.435 --> 01:11:32.310
has an incredible
business model,

01:11:32.310 --> 01:11:34.740
and it's got great growth
opportunities, et cetera.

01:11:34.740 --> 01:11:36.630
So is my variant
perception that I

01:11:36.630 --> 01:11:39.000
think you're going
to grow at 25% a year

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:41.140
over the next four
years, not 20% a year?

01:11:41.140 --> 01:11:44.327
Or that your margins are-- I
mean these are theoretical.

01:11:44.327 --> 01:11:45.910
These are things I
would want to test.

01:11:45.910 --> 01:11:50.310
Or is it my view that
a 20 or 25 multiple

01:11:50.310 --> 01:11:53.519
is too low for a company with
the world's second or best--

01:11:53.519 --> 01:11:55.810
or world's best or second
best economic characteristics

01:11:55.810 --> 01:11:57.750
and you really should
trade at 30 times earnings

01:11:57.750 --> 01:11:59.249
and the market will
figure that out.

01:11:59.249 --> 01:12:00.360
So I'm betting on that.

01:12:00.360 --> 01:12:04.240
Or am I betting that your
margins are depressed because

01:12:04.240 --> 01:12:07.460
of these very heavy investments
and stuff that's not currently

01:12:07.460 --> 01:12:10.090
paying a return, and that
these investments are

01:12:10.090 --> 01:12:12.220
going to taper down,
and therefore, margins

01:12:12.220 --> 01:12:14.550
are going to grow a bunch.

01:12:14.550 --> 01:12:17.730
I've got to believe
one of those things

01:12:17.730 --> 01:12:21.700
to buy one of the most
widely beloved largest market

01:12:21.700 --> 01:12:24.400
cap stocks in the world today.

01:12:24.400 --> 01:12:26.620
So that's probably
just in my gut.

01:12:26.620 --> 01:12:30.980
That's just not what I do as
a value investor to think,

01:12:30.980 --> 01:12:34.970
everybody loves this company,
but I love it even more.

01:12:34.970 --> 01:12:36.715
That rarely is a good
investment thesis.

01:12:36.715 --> 01:12:38.840
And that's not to say you
can't make a lot of money

01:12:38.840 --> 01:12:41.580
doing that-- riding
great companies.

01:12:41.580 --> 01:12:48.260
But I find it's better for me
to find a company that was once

01:12:48.260 --> 01:12:51.820
covered in glory-- Reed Hastings
was Fortune's Man of the Year

01:12:51.820 --> 01:12:54.900
or something like that
when the stock was at $300.

01:12:54.900 --> 01:12:59.170
And six months later,
the stock's down 80%.

01:12:59.170 --> 01:13:02.220
And I'm thinking, now
that's interesting.

01:13:02.220 --> 01:13:05.870
Is this company fundamentally
and completely broken,

01:13:05.870 --> 01:13:08.370
or did they screw some
things up and are they

01:13:08.370 --> 01:13:10.170
actually making a
really bold and bad,

01:13:10.170 --> 01:13:12.220
and forgoing current
profitability

01:13:12.220 --> 01:13:16.560
to drive a long-term
winner-take-all global market

01:13:16.560 --> 01:13:17.650
that they could dominate?

01:13:17.650 --> 01:13:21.180
And it's a rational short-term
decision to take profitability

01:13:21.180 --> 01:13:24.755
from $4 a share to $0.20 a
share in one year, to invest,

01:13:24.755 --> 01:13:26.230
to buy streaming content.

01:13:26.230 --> 01:13:28.027
To make that
incredibly bold bet.

01:13:28.027 --> 01:13:29.610
Amazon's been doing
that for 20 years.

01:13:29.610 --> 01:13:30.830
They've never made a
profit because they

01:13:30.830 --> 01:13:33.230
have a policy of taking
every single penny of profit

01:13:33.230 --> 01:13:35.150
and plowing it back
in to future growth.

01:13:35.150 --> 01:13:38.260
And you know what, the market
hasn't destroyed Amazon stock.

01:13:38.260 --> 01:13:40.960
But Netflix, they were selling
an earnings growth story,

01:13:40.960 --> 01:13:43.440
and then they decided the hell
with earnings growth, hell

01:13:43.440 --> 01:13:44.315
with earnings at all.

01:13:44.315 --> 01:13:46.023
We're just going to
invest in the future.

01:13:46.023 --> 01:13:47.210
We're become like Amazon.

01:13:47.210 --> 01:13:49.585
And all the investors that
were in there for the earnings

01:13:49.585 --> 01:13:50.950
interest story sold the stock.

01:13:50.950 --> 01:13:52.533
But I was like, you
know what, I think

01:13:52.533 --> 01:13:55.190
this company could be
a world beater someday.

01:13:55.190 --> 01:13:58.880
So that's more the kind
of situation I look for.

01:13:58.880 --> 01:14:01.650
But being real clear
what does the market

01:14:01.650 --> 01:14:04.450
believe today, you better
believe something different,

01:14:04.450 --> 01:14:06.540
you better understand
what the market believes,

01:14:06.540 --> 01:14:10.730
you better be right
in what you believe.

01:14:10.730 --> 01:14:11.560
Yeah.

01:14:11.560 --> 01:14:14.760
AUDIENCE: So looking at
fund as a whole, if you

01:14:14.760 --> 01:14:17.300
drop 50%, that's a
disaster because you've

01:14:17.300 --> 01:14:20.320
got to go 100% up just to
get back where you were.

01:14:20.320 --> 01:14:22.560
In a situation like
today where you

01:14:22.560 --> 01:14:24.940
might think that
there's a bubble--

01:14:24.940 --> 01:14:26.770
I mean it's hard
to find bargains.

01:14:26.770 --> 01:14:28.370
People are very optimistic.

01:14:28.370 --> 01:14:31.120
What do you do with your fund?

01:14:31.120 --> 01:14:37.670
How do you protect yourself
against a very large loss,

01:14:37.670 --> 01:14:41.597
which is much more likely
at a situation like now?

01:14:41.597 --> 01:14:43.430
WHITNEY TILSON: Well,
you have a short book.

01:14:43.430 --> 01:14:45.479
I'm a hedge fund, so
I'm short some stocks,

01:14:45.479 --> 01:14:47.520
and that will hopefully
protect me in a downturn.

01:14:47.520 --> 01:14:51.306
The problem is shorting's an
extremely difficult business.

01:14:51.306 --> 01:14:53.680
As hard as long investing is,
short investing is twice as

01:14:53.680 --> 01:14:55.880
hard for a variety of
reasons-- structural,

01:14:55.880 --> 01:14:58.070
but also your winners
become a bigger

01:14:58.070 --> 01:15:00.610
portion of your portfolio,
losses are unlimited,

01:15:00.610 --> 01:15:01.319
gains are capped.

01:15:01.319 --> 01:15:03.610
Unlike long investing, which
is the reverse, et cetera,

01:15:03.610 --> 01:15:04.150
et cetera

01:15:04.150 --> 01:15:06.108
I highly recommend that
you never short a stock

01:15:06.108 --> 01:15:07.182
your entire life.

01:15:07.182 --> 01:15:09.140
Just trust me, I've been
doing it for 12 years.

01:15:09.140 --> 01:15:10.240
I have an entire presentation.

01:15:10.240 --> 01:15:11.240
I can come back next week.

01:15:11.240 --> 01:15:12.960
I'll give you my
presentation on Lessons

01:15:12.960 --> 01:15:14.340
From A Dozen Years
of Short Selling

01:15:14.340 --> 01:15:16.923
I presented at Stanford Business
School-- to Stanford Business

01:15:16.923 --> 01:15:18.620
School students last night.

01:15:18.620 --> 01:15:19.540
Don't do it.

01:15:19.540 --> 01:15:23.840
So then, OK, well,
smart guy, the one thing

01:15:23.840 --> 01:15:25.350
that is sort of
obvious, you just

01:15:25.350 --> 01:15:27.990
have a short book
offsetting your long book.

01:15:27.990 --> 01:15:29.060
What do you do?

01:15:29.060 --> 01:15:32.600
The real answer is just buy
super high quality companies

01:15:32.600 --> 01:15:34.920
that can continue
to grow earnings

01:15:34.920 --> 01:15:37.170
and so forth, even during
economic downturns.

01:15:37.170 --> 01:15:39.690
And you buy them at
moderate multiples.

01:15:39.690 --> 01:15:43.100
And then just be willing to
accept the market pukes out,

01:15:43.100 --> 01:15:45.670
your stock's going
to go down in line

01:15:45.670 --> 01:15:47.210
with-- maybe in
line with market.

01:15:47.210 --> 01:15:48.465
Hopefully, if you buy
quality companies,

01:15:48.465 --> 01:15:50.350
it's a reasonable price, a
little less than the market.

01:15:50.350 --> 01:15:51.050
But you just have to
understand, if you're

01:15:51.050 --> 01:15:53.230
going to invest in stocks,
there's going to be volatility.

01:15:53.230 --> 01:15:55.250
And there is no such thing
as a free lunch where

01:15:55.250 --> 01:15:58.090
you get equity upside, but
you have no risk of downside.

01:15:58.090 --> 01:16:03.000
So don't invest in stocks if you
can't stomach some volatility.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:05.009
So there's no real
easy answer there.

01:16:05.009 --> 01:16:06.467
I don't recommend
you short stocks.

01:16:06.467 --> 01:16:09.880
I don't recommend you go out
and buy short-term S&amp;P 500 putts

01:16:09.880 --> 01:16:11.380
and roll them every month.

01:16:11.380 --> 01:16:12.520
Some hedge funds do that.

01:16:12.520 --> 01:16:14.930
And you're just
destroying capital.

01:16:14.930 --> 01:16:18.080
Generally speaking,
during times like this,

01:16:18.080 --> 01:16:22.750
invest more conservatively,
hold more cash,

01:16:22.750 --> 01:16:25.640
and take smaller position sizes.

01:16:25.640 --> 01:16:28.330
And just be patient.

01:16:28.330 --> 01:16:30.320
The markets come
and go in cycles.

01:16:30.320 --> 01:16:33.630
And most investors
are pro-cyclical.

01:16:33.630 --> 01:16:37.010
They pile into stocks in October
of '07, and then they puke it

01:16:37.010 --> 01:16:40.170
all out because they can't
take the pain in March of '09.

01:16:40.170 --> 01:16:42.200
They piled in
April of 2000, they

01:16:42.200 --> 01:16:47.110
piled out in October of 2002.

01:16:47.110 --> 01:16:50.300
So investors'
portfolios, as a rule,

01:16:50.300 --> 01:16:52.340
tend to do worse than
the overall market

01:16:52.340 --> 01:16:54.590
because their market
timing is so horrible.

01:16:54.590 --> 01:16:58.370
You need to be counter-cyclical,
and that's important.

01:16:58.370 --> 01:16:59.970
You either need to
be steady-- look,

01:16:59.970 --> 01:17:04.754
just put $10,000 every
quarter from your IRA,

01:17:04.754 --> 01:17:06.920
just put it into an [INAUDIBLE]
fund just quarterly,

01:17:06.920 --> 01:17:10.180
and it's sort of automatic,
you don't think about, right?

01:17:10.180 --> 01:17:12.400
That's a lot better than
what most investors do,

01:17:12.400 --> 01:17:13.964
which is being pro-cyclical.

01:17:13.964 --> 01:17:16.130
But ideally, you sort of
want to be counter-cyclical

01:17:16.130 --> 01:17:17.230
and just sort of
have an instinct.

01:17:17.230 --> 01:17:18.410
Look, I'm not a
full-time investor.

01:17:18.410 --> 01:17:19.140
I'm doing my job.

01:17:19.140 --> 01:17:20.010
I'm earning an income.

01:17:20.010 --> 01:17:21.510
I'm probably not
going to get fired.

01:17:21.510 --> 01:17:23.880
But the market's crapping
out, so maybe I'll

01:17:23.880 --> 01:17:25.749
bump that to
$20,000 this quarter

01:17:25.749 --> 01:17:28.040
and take a little bit of
money and put some extra money

01:17:28.040 --> 01:17:29.720
into the market.

01:17:29.720 --> 01:17:31.860
Maybe you put a
little bit less in.

01:17:31.860 --> 01:17:35.220
If you can do that over a
lifetime, that'll help a lot.

01:17:35.220 --> 01:17:37.220
JOHN HEINS: I wouldn't
overestimate your ability

01:17:37.220 --> 01:17:40.720
to time, however.

01:17:40.720 --> 01:17:42.740
I wouldn't overestimate
my ability to time.

01:17:42.740 --> 01:17:44.766
It's very difficult
to get that right.

01:17:44.766 --> 01:17:45.640
WHITNEY TILSON: Yeah.

01:17:45.640 --> 01:17:48.850
80% of the way there, if
you simply don't screw it up

01:17:48.850 --> 01:17:50.400
and you just do it steadily.

01:17:50.400 --> 01:17:54.230
And if you're really
clever-- I'm being-- look,

01:17:54.230 --> 01:17:56.930
I have done, in 16
years, I have done

01:17:56.930 --> 01:18:03.580
well by being aggressive in
late 2002 right after 9/11,

01:18:03.580 --> 01:18:06.470
at the bottom, late.

01:18:06.470 --> 01:18:10.190
You can actually-- there's
a public record of it.

01:18:10.190 --> 01:18:12.050
You can Google Whitney
Tilson "60 Minutes,"

01:18:12.050 --> 01:18:15.904
and in December of
2008, I correctly

01:18:15.904 --> 01:18:18.320
predicted the housing, the
bursting in the housing bubble,

01:18:18.320 --> 01:18:20.450
and I was a guest on "60
Minutes," about the housing

01:18:20.450 --> 01:18:20.950
crisis.

01:18:20.950 --> 01:18:22.480
And I said, I'm piling in.

01:18:22.480 --> 01:18:25.190
Like I'm all in, because as
bad as things are out there,

01:18:25.190 --> 01:18:26.850
stocks are cheap.

01:18:26.850 --> 01:18:30.860
So having that-- I
mean I'll tell you,

01:18:30.860 --> 01:18:33.520
because when you
feel like hiding

01:18:33.520 --> 01:18:35.180
under your desk
with a flak helmet

01:18:35.180 --> 01:18:37.940
on because every single day
your portfolio's blowing up,

01:18:37.940 --> 01:18:41.700
and the headlines are so
horrible, it's hard to do.

01:18:41.700 --> 01:18:46.020
But being counter-cyclical like
that, a contrarian like that

01:18:46.020 --> 01:18:46.830
can add value.

01:18:46.830 --> 01:18:48.210
But most people can't do it.

01:18:48.210 --> 01:18:50.690
So at the very least,
don't screw it up

01:18:50.690 --> 01:18:54.080
by doing what most people
do and piling in at the top

01:18:54.080 --> 01:18:56.527
and selling at the bottom.

01:18:56.527 --> 01:18:57.860
MALE SPEAKER: We're out of time.

01:18:57.860 --> 01:18:58.750
Thank you so much.

01:18:58.750 --> 01:18:59.550
WHITNEY TILSON: OK, thank you.

